<TITLE> Guess the Bureaucracy:  Week 2</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<CENTER><H2>Guess the Bureaucracy</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
This week's Town Hall Spotlight provides you with the chance to learn a little bit about some more of the organizations that run on your hard earned money--government bureaucracies--and win a Town Hall t-shirt in the process.  
<ol>
<li>Read the hints next to each picture.  
<li>Click on the picture to view a larger image.  
<li>Fill in your guess in the box next to each picture.
<li>Submit the form.  One lucky person will be chosen randomly from among those who guess every agency correctly to win a Town Hall T-shirt!
<li>Check back next week, when we'll label and link to each bureacracy and relevant articles from Town Hall Citizen Organizations.   
<li>More bureaucracies were featured in last week's Spotlight, and they are now labeled and linked to relevant articles.  <a href="/townhall/infotain/12-11-95/answers.html">Check it out!</a>  We will do the same to this set of bureaucracies next week, so be sure to check back in.

</ol>
<form method="POST" action="/townhall/scripts/form-handler.cgi">
<br>
<input name="01name" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> Name<br>        
<input name="02address" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> Address<br>
<input name="03city" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> City<br>
<input name="04state" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> State or Country    <br>
<input name="05zip" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> ZIP Code<br>
<SELECT name="08T-size"> 
<OPTION> L
<OPTION> XL
</select> Preferred T-Shirt Size
<P>
<input name="06e-mail address" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> E-mail address<br>
<input name="07how found TH" type="TEXT" value="" rows="1" size="36"> How did you hear about Town Hall?

<P>
<hr><P>
<br>

<A HREF="8.jpg"><IMG SRC="8.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="8" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul>
<li>Note:  This photo is of an auxiliary building, not the main one.
<li>This department was created in 1966 to oversee the growth in urban mass transit programs, air traffic, and construction of the Interstate Highway System.
<li>Because each member of Congress tries to assure that his or her state or district recieve as much pork as possible, this department regularly funds expensive, low-priority projects over more sensible, appropriate ones.
<li>Congress earmaked 129 surface projects, at an annual cost of $250 million in FY 1995. During the same year, $1.5 billion was appropriated for airport grants-in-aid, including nearly $5 million for the Jimmy Stewart Airport in Indiana County, Pennsylvania.
<li>19% (18,000 workers) of its civilian staff was furloughed in the first government shutdown.
</ul>

<A HREF="9.jpg"><IMG SRC="9.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="9" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul>
<li>Made infamous in the 1980's for purchasing $12 "portable language inscribers" (a.k.a. "pencils"), $45 hammers, and $130 toilet seats, this bureaucracy has shaped up considerably in recent years.
<li>The Clinton Administration underfunded even its own Bottom-Up Review of this Department by $100 million in 1995, and neglected to budget for unexpected emergency actions, like the one to Haiti.
<li>258,000 civilian employees (31% of its overall staff), labelled non-essential, didn't show have to commute to this 5-sided building during the first shutdown.
</ul>

<hr width="50%">

<P><P>
<A HREF="10.jpg"><IMG SRC="10.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="10" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul>
<li>Sent home 34,600 workers (58% of civilian staff) during the first shutdown.
<li>Approval of the budget as passed will eliminate one of this department's highest-profile positions, the Surgeon General's Office.
<li>Is part of the largest spending bill Congress produces annually.
<li>Operates the NIH.
</ul>


<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="11.jpg"><IMG SRC="11.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="11" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul>
<li>Its operating costs have ballooned by over 800 percent in the last thirty years, but did cut its 1996 budget to $2.2 billion, down from $2.4 billion in 1995.
<li>It recently came under the same environmental and workplace regulations that had long been imposed on all other organizations nationwide.
<li>Its 1995 appropriations bill eliminated 2,350 positions, 8.6% of its workforce.
<li>Since November 1994, it has been "Under New Management."
</ul>

<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="12.jpg"><IMG SRC="12.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="12" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul>
<li>90% of its civilian staff was labelled non-essential during the shutdown in early November.
<li>This department is part of our maze of overlapping departments, bureaus, and agencies designed to win the Cold War.
<li>It oversees US foreign aid programs.
</ul>

<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="13.jpg"><IMG SRC="13.gif" ALT="PHOTO" align="left"></A><b>YOUR GUESS?</b><input name="13" type="text" rows="1" size="36"><br>
<ul>
<li>Note:  Looking for name of the building.
<li>Once contained the entire staff of its highest ranking official, but that staff now occupies two entire builings, each larger than this original structure.
<li>89% (357 employees) of its core staff and 82% (1,000) members of its agencies were deemed "non-essential" by the OMB.
<li>Will hopefully be frequented by an army of moving trucks come December, 1996.
</ul>


