<HEAD>

<title>  Second Thoughts On the Third Wave? -- PFF</title>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Mike Manning">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Second Thoughts On the Third Wave?</h2>
<b>Progress On Point
<br>Periodic Commentaries on the Policy Debate
</b><P>
<i>Release 1.3 Nov 95                                        
                   </i>
<P>
By <a href="people/afellow.html#Pitsch">Peter K. Pitsch</a>
</center><P><P>
<i> &quot;Well, I think in the information age, too much information
and too much sort-of-quasi-information -- I mean, you guys have
to compete with near-news, too -- It's like, you know, like when
we were kids, we'd drink near-beer?  You've got all this information
and a lot competition among news sources and then you're competing
with the near-news and there is a danger that too much stuff cramming
in on people's minds is just as bad for them as too little in
terms of their ability to understand.&quot;
   </i>   <br><b>-- President Clinton</b>
<br>
               <I>The Washington Post</I>, 
                September 24, 1995
<P><hr width="50%">
<p> &quot;Too much information?&quot;  &quot;Near-news?&quot;  &quot;Ability
to understand?&quot;  In these informal remarks to a group of
reporters and producers, President Clinton appears to be having
second thoughts on the &quot;third wave&quot;.   In sharp contrast,
many commentators herald the much-acclaimed information revolution
precisely because it will empower individuals to convey and receive
their own news and information.  Who's right?  Are the many on-line
services, the Internet, talk radio and the sheer increase in electronic
outlets and programs a good thing?  More particularly, will they
lead to a more informed citizenry?
<P>
 There's no denying that Americans now enjoy an ever-expanding
range of outlets from which they can get a wealth of news and
information programming.  Focusing only on the electronic media,
98 percent of all U.S. homes can receive the major TV networks,
of which we now have four.  More than 90 percent of all households
can subscribe to cable TV and roughly 60 percent do.  Eighty-five
percent of all U.S. homes have VCRs.  Almost all can subscribe
to two one-hundred-channel direct broadcast TV systems (DBS) and
over a million have done so in the space of a year.  Ninety-four
percent of Americans can receive more than five TV  stations,
most of which carry locally originated programming.  By subscribing
to either cable or DBS, they can have more than a 100 additional
networks of information and programming.  Increasingly, AM radio
stations are adopting talk radio formats.  Local or nationally-syndicated
talk show hosts are giving millions of Americans the opportunity
to listen and discuss the issues of the day with  each other.
 Anyone with a telephone line, at least a 286 computer and modem
can access an online service and the Internet.  The three biggest
online services claim over 8 million subscribers and the entry
of Microsoft's new online service has caused sharp price reductions.
 
<P>
 Not surprisingly, this period of unprecedented change and opportunity
is causing many new companies to enter the market while others
are consolidating or forming alliances with each other.  Notably,
some of the nation's largest telephone companies are preparing
to enter the video market using their own facilities or recently
acquired radio frequencies.  At the same time they are forming
their own production companies and forming alliances with the
owners of existing programs.  Recently, three big networks, CBS,
ABC and TBS, have been acquired by large media companies.  
<P>
 Paradoxically, these developments have created two competing
sets of concerns for those leery of the ongoing changes in the
marketplace of ideas.  On the one hand, there are the President's
worries that the quality of the public debate is declining.  For
example, will the plethora of news sources make it too difficult
to carry on a coherent national discussion?  Do the talk show
and online discussions too often stray from the facts?  Or are
they too shrill, uncivil, or illiberal?  
<P>
 On the other hand, the Clinton Administration worries that the
House and Senate telecom bills  about to go to conference will
unduly relax statutory limitations on broadcast ownership.  Apparently,
the concern is that possible broadcast mergers may stymie public
debate by giving large companies too much control over the marketplace
of ideas.  Is the fear that we will then end up with too little
diversity of &quot;stuff cramming in on people's minds?&quot;
 
<P>
 Neither of these concerns is well-founded.  First, the Administration's
concern about media concentration is misplaced, especially if
the focus is on the broader marketplace of ideas.  Americans are
now enjoying  the benefits of more speakers than ever before even
if limited to traditional electronic media.  Given that the current
mergers are taking place in relatively unconcentrated markets
with low barriers to entry and are still subject to traditional
antitrust review, it is reasonable to assume that they are motivated
by the desire to become more efficient.  In competitive markets
any such improvements will largely benefit viewers and listeners,
often by improving program quality and diversity.  In addition
to existing competition, more and more Americans have wholly new
ways to express and receive ideas -- talk radio and online services
being two examples.
<P>
 Second, rather than be concerned that Americans are receiving
too much information which is reducing their ability to understand,
we should celebrate the new power Americans now enjoy to get news
and information.  This &quot;demassification&quot; of the media
(Alvin Toffler's term) will allow Americans, when they choose,
to get their news unfiltered through the established media.  This
is not to say that the reputation of news sources is not important.
 In fact, a speaker's trademark may become even more important
to listeners in the information age.  Listeners will continue
to have strong incentives to use trademarks and their own good
judgment to discern quality speech and speakers from the rest.
 What will be different is that a speaker's cost of reaching widespread
audiences has plummeted and will continue to fall.  
<P>
 This process is fundamentally healthy.  Old established speakers
with established franchises are and will continue to be challenged
by new sources.  Currently distrustful citizens will have alternatives
to turn to.  The old and the new media will criticize, check and
ultimately improve each other.  Remember the concerns the print
industry had regarding the introduction of radio?  Those who worry
about the onslaught of information and &quot;near news&quot; would
do well to remember the fundamental insight of Judge Learned Hand:
&quot;The First Amendment presupposes that the right conclusions
are more likely to be gathered out of a multitude of tongues,
than through any kind of authoritative selection.  To many this
is, and always will be, folly; but we have staked upon it our
all.&quot; 
<P><P>
<center>



</center></blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>

