<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Breaking the Telecom Logjam -- PFF</title>

</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>

<h2>Breaking the Telecom Logjam
</h2>
By <a href="/pff/people/director.html">G.A. Keyworth, II</a>
<P>
	As the House and Senate Conferees resolve the differences in the telecom bills passed by their respective bodies, they should keep one imperative in mind: "It's time to break the telecom logjam."  For the average American  these bills have undoubtedly gotten lost in a confusing swirl of competing claims and counterclaims about whether the bills will foster or undercut telephone competition.  Of late, the public discourse has been further confused by Clinton Administration contentions that the telecom bills would lead to undue media concentration and price gouging by cable TV companies.
<P>
	While widespread disaffection with this process would be understandable, a "pox on both your houses" attitude is a mistake.  The stakes for American consumers and workers in reforming telecom policy are immense.
<P>
	Starting in the mid-1970s Congress has time and again considered telecom legislation only to see the process stumble, stall and fail.  In this vacuum, the antitrust divestiture court, Federal Communications Commission, and the 50 states have set telecom policy.  At the national level, pro-competition policies were promoted by the divestiture court and the FCC.  Competition in the long distance, telephone equipment, and information services markets has flourished.  While some states have begun to open local telecom markets to competition, Congress now has a unique opportunity to jump-start this process by preempting state and local entry barriers and liberalizing related long distance, cable and broadcast regulation.  Congressional action would free up this dynamic sector and assure that the competitive process evolves naturally and produces a myriad of new digital services at the lowest possible cost.
<P>
	The importance of these coming contests is underscored by the many impressive preparations the combatants are undertaking to ready themselves to compete.  Most notable is AT&T's recent announcement that it will divest its network equipment business.  This second divestiture by AT&T will free it of any business conflicts with the Baby Bells who buy a lot of network equipment as it begins to compete in local telephone markets.  AT&T also has acquired McCaw Cellular, the largest independent cellular company, giving it the "wireless" capacity to compete with local telephone companies.  Also, a  consortia of cable companies and Sprint made winning bids of more than $2 billion in recent FCC auctions for wireless frequencies.  Finally, Hughes Satellite, Hubbard Broadcasting, Motorola and others have or will be embarking on satellite strategies.  These developments represent only a glimmer of the competitive energies that these telecom bills are about to unleash.
<P>
	The Clinton Administration and others claim that  passage of these bills would be a mistake.  They contend the bills will permit undue media concentration, lead to higher cable TV rates, and insufficiently guard against abuse by the Baby Bells of their local telephone monopoly.  These objections are either misplaced or can be worked out.
<P>
	The bills will not permit undue media concentration for two reasons.  First, all significant media mergers would still have to pass antitrust review.  Second, the radio and television markets (where the critics are most concerned) have seen hundreds of new stations come on line in the past five years, have low levels of concentration and face powerful challenges from competitors offering hundreds of channels, such as direct broadcast TV satellites (DBS), cable TV systems and telephone "video on demand" systems.
<P>
	Likewise, intrusive cable rate regulation is no longer productive.  Aside from the fact that cable faces competition from broadcast and DBS, cable regulation has simply not worked well.  It has been difficult for regulators to regulate cable systems, because cable prices are only one of several variables within the cable operator's control.  As a result cable rate regulation has likely led cable operators to reduce programming investment and quite possibly explains the failure of  the cable-telephone mega-mergers announced in 1993.
<P>
	The competitive issues implicated by the dispute between the local and long distance companies are admittedly more complex.  As much as we can be hopeful that local competition will flourish in most areas for most Americans, we are not there yet.  What preconditions the Baby Bell companies should meet before being allowed to enter the long distance market is something over which reasonable Nobel Laureates can disagree.  The House and Senate proposals are reasonable ones, though, and the time has come for the legislative leaders and President to cut the Gordian knot.
<P>
	These bills are not perfect by any means.  For example, they duck the important issues of reducing residential phone subsidies and freeing up radio spectrum use.  A Progress & Freedom Foundation study recommended these reforms as part of a fundamental reform package which would replace the Federal Communication Commission and rely even more on market forces.  These and other legislative improvements will have to await a "second" bite of the apple.
<P>
	Finally, there is no denying that these complicated bills evidence a lot of  "sausage-making."  Nonetheless, they replace a smorgasbord of federal law, FCC rules, divestiture court jurisprudence and state regulation.  In so doing, the telecom legislation would open local telephone markets to competition from long distance and cable TV companies, open the long distance market to competition from the Baby Bells, and open cable TV markets to competition from the local telephone company.  While many important issues would be left to the FCC and state regulators, reform along the lines of the bills would constitute a "great competitive leap forward."      
<P>
<i>G.A. Keyworth, II is chairman of the board of The Progress & Freedom Foundation and chairman of its Cyberspace and the American Dream Project.  The views expressed are solely those of the author.</i>
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
