<TITLE>Town Hall Spotlight:  Budget Reconciliation</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">  
<P>

<CENTER><a name="intro"></a> 

<H2>Budget Reconciliation<BR></CENTER></H2>

<HR><center><a href="#Misc">Spotlight on the budget reconciliation</a></center>
<P>
<P>
The much-touted "train wreck" has been averted with the adoption of continuing resolutions.  The House and Senate have passed their versions of the budget.  Now members from each house must meet to iron out a final package to send to President Clinton.
<P>
Both the House and Senate versions of the budget reduce the government's burden on citizens and introduce better incentives for savings and investment.  President Clinton has vowed to veto any budget that closely resembles those passed in the houses of Congress; some Republicans are in favor of allowing the budget ceiling to expire if Clinton refuses to move to the right.  Who will flinch first?  The political manuevering is bound to be exciting!  
<P>
This week, <b>Town Hall Spotlight</b> focuses on the final phase of the budget process:  conference.
<P>
On Monday, get a refresher on the budget process and what "conference" is.  You'll also be able to see our national debt, updated continuously, as well as review, line-by-line, last year's budget.  On Tuesday, we take a break from our budget coverage to bring you an election-day special.  On Wednesday our budget battle coverage resumes with links to and analysis of the two versions of this year's budget.  On Thursday, check out the politics behind the battle.  On Friday, e-mail the Budget Conferees with your opinions!  
<p>
Please share your opinions with us any day of the week by filling out our budget battle questionaire.  We hope you find these articles enlightening!





