<html><head><title>Budget Reconciliation Survey Results</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><h2><center>Budget Reconciliation Survey Results</center></h2><hr>
<a href="#comments">Selected Comments</a><P>
<b>Question:</b> Regardless of your registration, do you consider yourself a Republican or a Democrat?<P>Republican: 95%<br>Democrat: 5%
<P><b>Question:</b> Should the Republicans negotiate with the President or let him veto it, resulting in a government shutdown?<P>Negotiate:  13%<br>Let him veto: 87%
<p><b>Question</b> Do you think the Democratic Party has a chance to win back either the House or the Senate?<P>Yes: 29%<br>No: 61%
<p><b>Question</b> Do you believe the Republicans or the Democrats are more serious about balancing the budget?<p>Republicans: 96%<br>Democrats: 4%
<P><b>Question</b> Democrats accuse the Republicans of wanting to make draconian cuts in every aspect on our lives. Do you agree with their characterization?<P>Yes: 11%<br>No: 89%
<p><b>Question</b> Do you trust the Republicans to fight for a balanced budget regardless of any bad political fallout?<P>Yes: 61%<br>No: 29%
<p><p><hr><P>
<center><h3>Selected Comments</h3></center>
<a name="comments"></a>
<b>Comments:</b><P>

<ul>


Unfortunately, the budget issue is beginning to lose the attention of the voters.  In the end, success at the polls will not be determined by the poignancy of the issues, but by the amount of interest the issue can muster among voters.  And so, light weight stupid issues like school prayer and smut on the internet become the cause d'jour while important matters like the solvency of our economy are neglected.<br><b>Mark, Staten Island, NY</b><P>

Just shut it down.<br>
It's time to call Clinton's and Paneta's bluff.
Keep up the talk of the "irresponsibility of leaving more debt to our children"on top of the $5 trillion already spent.
<br>Enough is enough!<br><b>Dean, Portland, OR</b><p>

Republicans should stand fast.  Don't get political
cold feet.  You don't need to compromise.
Compromising your principles means violating them!!
That's not what we sent you there to do.
<BR>
Unfortunately, old-bulls like Bob Dole seem to have a
"principle of the day" - whatever seems to be popular.
These are not principles, so we would have to call
wavering Republicans such as Bob Dole unprincipled.
<BR>
I speak for myself and hundreds of others who are tired
of seeing the old-timers run scared from the media, and
the freshman ignored by the Republican leadership.
<BR>
Get your act together guys, or we'll put you out to
pasture as soon as possible!!!
<br><b>Ron, St. Louis, MO</b>
<P>
The Democrats obviously have no desire to balance the budget. They are only playing along because they want to appear to be part of the process. If the Republicans had not gained a majority there would no talk of balanced budget, or welfare reform or Medicare reform from the Democrats. The Republicans should ignore the polls for the next year and keep pushing their budget reform. If the Republicans faulter at this there is a danger of the Democrats retaking the Congress.<br><b>Mark, Pasadena, CA</b><P>

Ronald Reagan once told his budget director, Jim Miller, "Jim, let's just shut it down, and see whether anyone notices!"<br><b>Terry, Toms River, NJ</b><P>

Please DO NOT raise the national DEBT ceiling 1 dollar on our children and grandchildren. I believe AS HAS ALREADY panned out in the media that the Republicians can make NO deals with either the Democrats or the President. Therefore I suggest a strong hand approach in dealing with him, DON'T BUDGE ONE INCH, give him the bills then adjurn congress and go home and let him squell. A week or two of no budget wont cause America to go under,and Him, Morris and his other handlers and so called experts can just scream. Get tuff with the media, show them that Clinton and Dems wont compromise, do your own media blitz. He has already stated he does not like this or that in the bills, face it at every turn he will make Congress look bad, SO PLAY HARDBALL with him. If he calls you back from adjournment TAKE YOUR TIME getting back, let Clinton be the GRINCH THAT STOLE CHRISTMAS. I have learned that NASTY people can only be delt with from a STRONG position and NEVER, NEVER compromise unless THEY are willing to also compromise.<br><b>William, Frederick, MD</b><P>

Quit the cutbacks and start cutting whole departments!
Any bureaucracy not eliminated while we have the chance
will just "grow" itself back within a decade or three.<br><b>Mike, Little Rock, AR</b><P>

 I'm very anxious about the 4.8 trillion dollar dept; particulary when I contemplate the future for my children. As a middle class income earner, I find the tax burden excessive, and quite frankly I'm getting physically and mentally tired. I want the federal government to be downsized, the states to be empowered, and my taxes restributed with more staying in my state.<br><b>Robert, Sierra Vista, AZ</b><P>

Republicans have lost some credibility with me by failing to address some of the more egregious examples of the so-called corporate welfare and special interest subsidies.  But the party has to remain firm in its convictions and continue to stress the benefits of the budget package without feeling that they must respond to the criticisms of the left.
<br>Stay the high ground.<br><b>James, Centerville, OH</b><p>

The Republicans in Congress must stand fast!  They must
withstand the barrage of the criticism of desperate
liberals.  Let Clinton save face by "negotiating" with him 
and making minor conciliations that he can then gloat
over.  As long as the result is a balanced budget, the
citizens of this country are the real winners.<br><b>Louise, Menlo Park, CA</b><P>


















</ul><P><b>Thanks to everyone who participated in our survey!<P><P>[ <a href="/townhall/welcome.html.cgi">Town Hall Home</a> | <a href="/townhall/cyber_personth/welcome.html">Town Hall Spotlights</a> ] 
