<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Algeria</TITLE>
<H2 >ALGERIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>   	The North African country of Algeria has had a state-controlled socialist economy since 
independence from France in 1962. Years of government mismanagement and low oil prices in the 
mid-1980s led to anti-government riots in 1988. In 1989, Algeria adopted a new constitution that 
ended one-party rule and called for multi-party elections. But the elections were canceled in January 
1992 after the results of the first round of voting made it clear that the radical Islamic Salvation 
Front would have taken power. This precipitated a rebellion by Islamic radicals against the military-
backed government. Since 1992, more than 10,000 Algerians have been killed in a brutal civil war. 
Islamic terrorists have targeted foreigners to cut Algeria's economic links to the outside world and to 
fuel discontent. In this uncertain climate, real economic growth has averaged barely 2 percent per 
year over the last several years. Under pressure from the international financial community, Algeria 
has committed to economic liberalization. The pursuit of economic reform, however, has been 
erratic.
<P><IMG SRC="alg.gif"> 
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B> <BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Algeria has been liberalizing its trade policy. Substantial barriers to free trade nonetheless 
remain. Lately the government has shown some signs of backtracking, tightening import 
controls, for example. Nevertheless, the government monopoly on trade has been 
abolished. The government reformed the tariff schedule in 1992, cutting the top tariff rate 
from 120 percent to 60 percent as well as reducing the number of tariff categories. In 
addition to tariffs, importers must pay two other taxes, adding a combined 17 percent to 90 
percent to the cost of imports. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>    Some goods require import licenses.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B> <BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5- Stable (High tax rates)</I>
The top income tax rate in Algeria is 50 percent. There is no tax on average income. Income 
earned by foreigners is taxed at a flat 20 percent. It had been as high as 70 percent. The 
corporate tax rate is 50 percent for business profits and 20 percent for earnings that are 
reinvested. Tax breaks are available for companies locating in poorer areas. Algeria also 
maintains a value-added tax of 21 percent. 
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
State-controlled enterprises dominate most commerce and industry. Private sector involvement 
is slowly increasing. The government consumes 16.9 percent of Algeria's GDP. Algeria's 
state sector is massive, accounting for some 65 percent of national production. 
Unfortunately, massive corruption and mismanagement permeate the government. An 
announced privatization effort has not progressed.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 2- (Low inflation rate) </I><BR>
Algeria's average annual rate of inflation between 1980 and 1991 was 10.1 percent. Inflation 
was estimated at 24 percent for 1993. 
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Algeria has recently improved its foreign investment environment. A 1993 investment code 
includes incentives for foreign investors, though the wording is vague. Laws governing 
hydrocarbons and natural gas exploration have been liberalized and free trade zones have 
been established. Nevertheless, several sectors remain off limits to foreigners. Coupled with 
the large role of state enterprises, foreign investment opportunities remain limited. 
Moreover, it is not uncommon for foreign investors to spend two years negotiating with 
government officials who oversee investments. Finally, radical Islamic groups are 
threatening the stability of the government. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Algeria's heavily state-controlled banking sector has been liberalized. Foreign banks may 
establish operations in Algeria. They must maintain the same level of capital as Algerian 
banks. Two private Algerian banks are in the process of being formed. The state-owned 
central bank assumes non-performing commercial bank loans, many of which are carried 
by state-controlled enterprises.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate wage and price controls) </I><BR>
The Algerian government controls the profit margins and the sales of  medicine, school 
supplies, tobacco, sugar, coffee, and vegetable oil. Subsidies on food items exist, and the 
government's widespread participation in the economy limits pricing competition. However, 
some prices have been decontrolled over the last few years.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-  (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Government expropriation is unlikely. Algerian law prohibits expropriation based upon future 
legislation. Expropriations based upon existing law require fair compensation in foreign 
currency. Of late, collective farms have been parceled into lease properties. This is a 
modest advance for property rights. Overall, private property is reasonably well protected 
in Algeria. This would change drastically if the Islamic fundamentalists were to come to 
power. 
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-  (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Algerian private sector enterprises, of which there are relatively few, must contend with 
burdensome regulations. Algerian workers cannot be easily dismissed. The norm is 
employment for life. This represents a considerable burden to foreign companies and the 
private sector. In addition, it is difficult for foreign companies to hire people from their 
home country. Paying taxes is cumbersome, partly because of the inefficient and corrupt 
bureaucracy.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
A punishing tax structure drives many private sector transactions into the black market. 
<P><B>Summary</B>

<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.15  

Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 3  
</PRE>

 <P>
<P>   
<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>  
<P>[1]  Algeria's average tariff rate was unavailable.
</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
