<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Australia</TITLE>
<H2>AUSTRALIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	An agrarian economy for most of its history, since the late 1970s Australia has made great 
strides in deregulation and opening its economy to foreign trade. The 1980s saw the privatization of 
many government-owned corporations and financial deregulation. And once highly protected, 
Australia has dismantled hefty barriers to trade and almost eliminated subsidies to agriculture. 
Today Australia is a leading force seeking trade liberalization in the GATT and the emerging Asia 
Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
<P><IMG SRC="aus.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Australia has an average tariff rate of less than 4 percent. Nevertheless, it maintains high tariffs 
on some items, such as a 32.5 percent duty on automobiles. Moreover, import quotas exist 
for textiles, apparel, and footwear.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Australia has a top income tax rate of 47 percent. The average income level is taxed at a rate of 
20 percent. The top corporate tax rate is 33 percent. Australia has a 33 percent capital gains 
tax and an 11 percent to 31 percent sales tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The Australian government consumes about 19 percent of GDP. The government plays a 
significant role in such industries as energy and transportation.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Australia had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 7 percent. In 1992 it was 
1.5 percent, and in 1993 and 1994 inflation remained stable at around 3 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Australia has opened its economy to foreign investment. It provides equal treatment for 
domestic and foreign firms. It has also opened particular services industries like insurance 
and accounting to some foreign participation.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks in Australia are relatively free from intrusive government control. Foreigners are allowed 
to establish wholly owned institutions or branches.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Wages and prices are mainly determined by the market. Minimum wages are not established 
across the board, but they may exist for some government contract projects, such as in 
construction. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is very secure in Australia. It has an efficient legal and judicial system that enforces 
contracts and settles disputes. Government expropriation is very unlikely.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Some regulations are cumbersome, especially those affecting labor, occupational safety and 
health standards, and the environment.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Australia has a small black market in labor services. Some workers try to evade taxes by 
working directly for cash.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.20</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 1  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
