<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Bolivia</TITLE>
<H2>BOLIVIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Bolivia is a landlocked country in central South America. It is a constitutional democracy. 
While much of Latin America is moving toward liberalized economies and free trade, the 
government still maintains a strong hold on the economy. While the government has controlled 
inflation and the economy has grown somewhat, Bolivia is behind its neighbors in economic growth 
and freedom. In fact, Bolivia is the poorest country in South America.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism)</I><BR>
In 1990, the government reduced the average tariff rate from 16 percent to 10 percent on all 
but capital goods, whose rate is 5 percent. Thus, Bolivia's average tariff rate is between 5 
percent and 9 percent.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2+ (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Bolivia has a flat income tax rate of 13 percent. It does not tax corporate income. Instead, it 
taxes corporations based on their net worth, at a rate of 3 percent. Bolivia also has a 13 
percent value-added tax and a variety of other transaction and property taxes.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Bolivia's government consumes more of its economy than does any other state in South 
America. State-owned industries account for over 70 percent of GDP. Government 
consumption as a percentage of GDP is 16 percent.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
Bolivia has had chronically high inflation rates, though considerable progress has been made 
recently. Its average inflation rate was 264 percent from 1980 to 1991. In 1992 and 1993, 
the inflation rate fell to about 10 percent.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Foreign investment is encouraged in Bolivia. Few restrictions remain on foreign investment. 
While some restrictions remain on the petroleum and mining industries, they are minimal.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Bolivia's banking system is backward and corrupt. Most banks in Bolivia are state-controlled 
and lending is aimed at the state sector. There are only five foreign banks in Bolivia. Both 
private and foreign banks are restricted by the government.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
There are few price controls in Bolivia, although the government maintains the right to impose 
limits on the prices of foodstuffs. Wages and prices are becoming more free as more state-
owned companies have been privatized. There are no minimum wage laws in Bolivia.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Legal protection of private property is lax. Large property owners are particularly vulnerable to 
official corruption as property can be seized without just compensation and "taxed" by 
corrupt government officials. Although the government has begun an ambitious 
privatization program, expropriation of private property is still possible.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of government regulation)</I><BR>
Bolivia's economy is heavily regulated through haphazardly applied government requirements 
on business. There are many complaints of corruption. While the government maintains no 
occupational or environmental regulations, corruption poses a significant burden on 
business.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Bolivia has one of the largest black markets in the Western Hemisphere. The black market is 
about equal to the official economy of Bolivia. Much of this black market is in the drug 
trade. Still, Bolivia's regulations push many "legal" professions into the black market, such 
as construction, transportation, and others.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.20</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 4  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 1  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

