<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Botswana</TITLE>
<H2>BOTSWANA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Southern African country of Botswana was named a British protectorate in 1885. The 
country remained under the protection of Britain until 1966 when it was granted independence. 
Botswana is sparsely populated. Wealth is very sharply divided between rich and poor. Botswana is 
highly dependent on bordering South Africa, which supplies about 85 percent of its imports and 
even administers the country's customs procedures.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Botswana has moderately high tariffs but few, if any, non-tariff barriers. The average tariff rate 
is 19.4 percent. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Botswana has a top marginal income tax rate of 40 percent. The rate that applies to the average 
income level is zero percent. Botswana has a top corporate income tax of 40 percent. 
<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>   It also has a 40 percent capital gains tax, a 10 percent 
sales tax, and a 35 percent capital transfer tax which covers such transfers as inheritance. 
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Botswana has a rather high rate of government consumption in the economy. The government 
consumes 34.9 percent of the Botswanan GDP. <FONT SIZE="-2">[3]</FONT>   
Moreover, the state sector owns a significant portion of the country's enterprises. 
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of inflation)</I><BR>
The average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 13.2 percent. Inflation was about 12 
percent in 1993.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
There are many sectors of the economy that are closed to foreign investment. These are: 
agriculture, bakeries, cement, postal services, railways, retail merchandising, 
telecommunications, textiles, and water. Most foreign investors are treated the same as 
domestic businesses. There are some tax holidays for specific investments.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Botswana has a competitive and advanced banking system compared to most African nations. 
However, the state plays a heavy role in the banking system by controlling most banks 
through the state-owned and -operated central banking system. Foreign banks are not 
permitted to operate in Botswana. The government owns and manages several major 
commercial banks.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most wages and prices are determined by the market. Botswana has a minimum wage. Few 
prices are set by the government. However, agriculture prices are established by negotiated 
agreements with the government. Moreover, since a large portion of the economy is owned 
by the government, both prices and wages are affected by government-determined wage 
and price policies.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Property is relatively safe in Botswana. There is little history of property expropriation in 
Botswana. However, because of poor economic conditions, the court system lacks the 
money to operate the courts efficiently.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
Despite Botswana's free market orientation, government bureaucracy often poses a burden on 
businesses. A business license is relatively easy to obtain. However, the bureaucracy plays 
a significant role in running the economy. For example, the government regulates the length 
of the work week, maternity leave, and standards for hiring and firing. This is burdensome 
for businesses.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
By African standards, Botswana's black market is moderately sized. Some activities, mainly in 
services like construction, occur in the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>

<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.05</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This rate is based on IMF figures. The taxes on international trade are computed as a percentage 
of total imports for 1991.<BR>
[2]  The basic corporate tax rate is 30 percent, but some companies pay an additional 10 percent 
tax.<BR>
[3]  This figure is derived by computing central government expenditures for 1991 as a percentage of 
GDP.
</FONT>


<BR>
