<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Cameroon</TITLE>
<H2>CAMEROON</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Germany, the United Kingdom, and France all laid colonial claims on the sub-Saharan 
African country of Cameroon.  By 1961, the country had gained its independence from all 
European powers. A one-party state was established soon afterwards and political repression 
followed. By 1992, increasing pressure for democratization resulted in democratic elections and the 
creation of a multi-party state.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
The average tariff rate is around 30 percent. Almost 40 percent of government revenues are 
raised through these tariffs. Cameroon also uses countervailing and antidumping duties to 
protect its inefficient domestic industries.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Cameroon has a top income tax rate of 66 percent. The tax rate on the average income level is 
10 percent. Cameroon has a top corporate tax rate of 38.5 percent. Cameroon also has a 
38.5 percent capital gains tax and a 10.9 percent turnover tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Cameroon's government consumes 13.3 percent of GDP. It has a large public sector that is 
inefficient and corrupt.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Cameroon had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 4.5 percent. Inflation ran 
around 3 percent in 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Cameroon has opened its borders to foreign investment, but it remains partial to investments 
from France and in some cases blocks them from other countries. Furthermore, 
Cameroon's corrupt bureaucracy and unstable legal institutions provide little comfort to 
foreign investors.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks in Cameroon are heavily influenced by the state. Interest rates, for example, are 
controlled by the government and often do not reflect market conditions. However, there is 
a domestic banking industry.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
While most prices are set by the market, the government directly controls prices on some items. 
It does this by owning and operating enterprises, and it officially dictates the prices of  
some goods that are produced by private firms and farms. Cameroon has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property is not entirely safe in Cameroon. A corrupt government and an uncertain legal 
environment can result in the confiscation of private property. Crime threatens property 
and government expropriation is possible, but not probable. However, private property is 
legal.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Cameroon's economy is heavily regulated. Corruption is rampant. Existing regulations are 
applied unevenly and pose a huge burden for businesses.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Cameroon's black market is nearly as large as its legal one. Smugglers regularly bring in beef 
and other food products to circumvent the government's 40 percent countervailing duty on 
agricultural products.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.50</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
