<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Chile</TITLE>
<H2>CHILE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	While most of the economic success stories since 1960 come from Asia, Chile is one 
shining example of a Western Hemispheric country enjoying great economic success. Chile 
underwent a massive economic transformation in the 1970s that has made it the envy of Latin 
America. This economic transformation continues and has resulted in some of the fastest economic 
growth rates in the Western Hemisphere. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   Following this 
steadfast economic transformation, Chile underwent a series of political reforms that culminated in 
democratic elections in 1989. The Chilean Constitution has well defined and protected individual 
liberties. Chile's new president, Eduardo Frei, is continuing the country's free market course.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
International trade is the cornerstone of the Chilean economy. Chile has a flat tariff rate for 
most products of 11 percent. However, other tariffs raise the average tariff rate to 12.37 
percent. Chile maintains an import license requirement, but only about 5 percent of the 
applications are rejected each year. Chile has substantial non-tariff barriers.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
The top income tax rate is 20 percent. The average taxpayer is in the 7 percent bracket. Chile's 
rates are among the lowest in Latin America. <FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>  Chile 
taxes its citizens under a complex method of increasing tax rates based on what the 
government calls the "value" of earnings. These values are determined by periodic 
calculations to limit the effects of inflation. Chile has an effective top corporate income tax 
rate of 35 percent. Chile also maintains a 15 percent capital gains tax and an 18 percent 
value-added tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low government consumption)</I><BR>
Chile is an example of how reduced government consumption produces solid rates of economic  
growth. Chile's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 8.6 percent. Chile has 
achieved this low rate by permitting private enterprises to  supply such "public" services as 
education, pension funds, social security, and some utilities. <FONT SIZE="-
2">[3]</FONT>   Chile's social security system, for example, is privately owned and 
operated.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate inflation rate)  </I><BR>
Chile's average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 20 percent. Chile's central bank 
pegs the peso to a basket of currencies based on the U.S. dollar.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Chile aims to attract foreign investors by granting them quick government approval in some 
industries. Nevertheless, while Chile has reformed its foreign investment code to attract 
investment, significant barriers still exist. For example, all foreign investors must gain 
permission from the government's Foreign Investment Committee. Moreover, the 
government maintains restrictions on investment in the fishing, maritime transport, and oil 
and gas industries. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
While Chile's banking system is relatively free from government corruption, it is not a totally 
competitive, market-oriented industry. Chile requires a license for foreign banks. All 
licenses have been frozen. Thus, no new foreign banks now are allowed in Chile. Only 20 
foreign banks operate in Chile. Domestic banks, especially those in the lending business, 
often find themselves in competition with the government-owned banks, thus distorting 
market operations. Chile has a state-operated agency that provides subsidized loans to the 
public and private sectors. Its 40 percent default rate has swallowed up lending capital and 
skewed the banking system with bad loans. Banks are not permitted to engage in insurance, 
real estate, or investment services.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Chile's price policy is determined mainly by the market. Some exceptions are prices for urban 
and public transport and some utilities. Minimum wages, hours worked, and safety 
regulations are all controlled by the government. Chile also maintains a "family subsidy" for 
poor workers, which guarantees a minimum wage for specified workers.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Private property is gaining increased protection from the Chilean government through greater 
efficiency in the court system and legal institutions. Chile has had since the early 1980s a 
comprehensive program of privatization, and it continues today. The likelihood of private 
property expropriation is very low.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation)</I><BR>
Government regulation in Chile runs from nonexistent in some areas to overbearing in others. 
Opening a business in Chile is far easier than in many Latin American countries. 
Regulations are moderate, but some can pose a burden on private businesses. The Public 
Health Ministry, for example, regulates all food and drug products. The Ministry directly 
regulates the production, storage, distribution, sale, and import of all food and drug items.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate black market activity)</I><BR>
Like most Latin American countries, Chile has a black market. Some estimates suggest that as 
much as 35 percent of the labor in Chile, especially in the bigger cities, is supplied by the 
black market. Nevertheless, as the country becomes more industrialized, the black market 
activities will shrink.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.50</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]"Economic and Social Progress in Latin America: 1993 Report," Inter-American Development Bank, Washington, D.C., 1993.<BR>
[2]  "Taxation in Latin America," KPMG, USA, 1990, pp. 19-25<BR>
[3]  Cristian V. Larroulet, ed., "The Chilean Experience: Private Solutions to Public Problems," Instituto 
Libertad Y Desarrollo and the Center for International Private Enterprise, Chile, 1991.
</FONT>
<BR>
