<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Congo</TITLE>
<H2>CONGO</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The central African county of Congo became a French colony in 1910. It became 
independent in 1960. Congo's history has been marked by one-party rule, political repression, 
economic stagnation, and frequent military coups. In 1992, multi-party elections were held. These 
elections spawned riots and civil unrest. Little progress toward democratic or market reforms has 
been made since.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Congo's average tariff rate is unknown. The biggest barrier to trade remains red tape, rampant 
corruption in the customs service, and outright theft of imported goods by government 
officials. This form of non-tariff barrier virtually closes the market to imports.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR> 
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Congo has a top income tax rate of 50 percent. The average income level is taxed at a rate of 
15 percent. The top corporate tax is 49 percent. Congo also has a 49 percent capital gains 
tax and a 16 to 20.5 percent goods and services tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Congo's government consumes 38.2 percent of GDP. Moreover, it has an extremely large 
state-owned sector.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Congo had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 0.4 percent. This increased to 
3.6 percent in 1992, dropping to 2.8 percent in 1993. It is estimated to be about 2.5 percent 
for 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Foreign investment is ruled by a government code. Foreign investors face hostile government 
bureaucrats and labor conditions. Many labor unions are still under the influence of Marxist 
ideology, making it nearly impossible to do business in the Congo.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks remain under the control and influence of corrupt government officials. Foreign banks 
are limited in their ability to operate in Congo by hostile labor conditions.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Prices are controlled through large government-owned companies which are subsidized by the 
government. There is a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Government expropriation of property remains possible. An insufficient judicial and legal 
framework results in little government protection of private property.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Government regulators are corrupt, often requiring bribes. Regulations are enforced 
haphazardly and pose a burden on business.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Congo's black market is large. Corruption by customs officials creates a market for smuggling 
of all types of goods.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.90</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
