<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Cuba</TITLE>
<H2>CUBA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Cuba is one of the most repressed economies in the world. After Fidel Castro seized power 
in 1959, he systematically imposed government control and ownership of every economic activity 
and outlawed private property and individual economic freedom. Cuba's economy remained afloat 
through decades of hefty subsidies from the Soviet Union, which used the island as a base to 
threaten U.S. national security. After the Soviet Union collapsed, Cuba lost its subsidies, forcing it 
to compete internationally on its own merits. Understandably, the Cuban economy collapsed. 
Although Castro has made some reforms to attract foreign investors, Cuba's economy is still 
communist.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Castro maintains some of the highest levels of protectionism in the world. All imports into Cuba 
must be inspected and approved by Castro's government. In many cases, customs officials 
confiscate imports for their own personal use, especially if they are scarce goods like 
electronics. Official corruption is sanctioned and supported by Castro's customs officials. 
As a result, Cuba has trade barriers that effectively bar most imports.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Because the Cuban government controls the entire economy, it essentially confiscates the 
proceeds of all economic activity.  Since the fruits of all economic activity are owned by 
the government, the resulting rate of taxation approaches 100 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of government consumption ) </I><BR>
Although Castro permits some private economic activity in a restricted way, the means of 
production and the profits gained from them are still entirely in the hands of the state. The 
Cuban government directly owns and runs most of the Cuban economy.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high levels of inflation) </I><BR>
The Castro government claims that inflation does not exist in Cuba.  But this is a fiction. If 
price controls were lifted and the true value of the currency were measured, inflation would 
be extremely high. The official prices of goods may be low because they are controlled and 
subsidized by the state, but the tremendous scarcity of goods and services attests to their 
real value. In short, Cuba's currency is worth little, and it is not convertible on the 
international market. Moreover, because money is printed rampantly to cover the costs of 
debts, the peso is greatly inflated. The Cuban government freely admits that 11.5 billion 
pesos are circulating in excess of demand. 
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Foreign investment is effectively barred in Cuba. Castro will permit some foreign investments, 
in tourism for example, but  the Cuban government outlaws full foreign ownership. 
Moreover, the Cuban foreign investment code is unreliable.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks in Cuba are owned and operated by the government and are heavily influenced by the 
state-owned central bank. There is no competition in this industry.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Virtually all wages and prices are set by the Cuban government.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property is outlawed in Cuba, and the government can confiscate property with 
impunity.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of regulation) </I><BR>
The Cuban government regulates the entire economy by owning and operating the means of 
production.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5- (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Cuba's black market activity is greater than that of the official or legal economy. As might be 
expected in a command economy, even basic economic activities are performed in the 
black market. Thus, Cuba's black market involves the sale of basic foodstuffs like milk and 
bread, transportation services, and housing.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 5.00</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 5  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 5  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 5  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 5  
Foreign Investment 5		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>


