<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Ecuador</TITLE>
<H2>ECUADOR</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Ecuador became independent from Spain in 1822. For the next century, the country was 
plagued by much instability and many dictatorships. Today, Ecuador's economy is based mainly on 
oil. During the oil boom of the 1970s, the government of Ecuador used its increased wealth to 
subsidize businesses and generally to raise the level of government consumption in the economy. 
However, as oil prices plummeted later in the decade and into the 1980s,  Ecuador's oil-based 
economy began to decline. Trying to recover, Ecuador has been making economic reforms that 
reduce the level of state intervention in the economy.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Ecuador's average tariff rate is 12 percent. Importers must obtain an import license that can 
delay the movement of goods into the country. In addition, customs procedures can often 
be very complicated and mired in bureaucratic red tape.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 2.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR
Ecuador has a top marginal income tax rate of 25 percent. The tax rate that applies to the 
average income level is zero percent. Ecuador's top tax rate on corporate profits is 25 
percent. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   In addition, Ecuador has a 25 percent capital 
gains tax and a 10 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Ecuador's government consumes only 8.7 percent of its GDP. This may seem very low 
considering the government employs 25 percent of the work force and many industries are 
dominated by state-owned firms. Yet the vast majority of firms are privately owned. The 
state-owned sector contributes less than 8 percent of GDP. 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5- (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
Ecuador's main monetary goal has been to stabilize inflation by controlling the supply of 
money. Yet Ecuador's average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 38 percent. 
The inflation rate in 1992 was 50 percent. Inflation ran at about 40 percent in 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
The Ecuadorian government has been liberalizing its foreign investment policies since 1990. 
Most investors are free to invest in almost any industry. Exceptions are in such so-called 
strategic industries as mining, and enterprises owned by the state.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
There are 32 private banks in Ecuador, which is a considerable number when compared to 
many of its neighbors. Ecuador has a large number of foreign banks. Domestically owned 
banks are relatively competitive with foreign banks. However, these privately owned banks 
must compete with state-owned development banks that provide a variety of subsidized 
loans to farmers, ranchers, and small businessmen. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Although there are fewer price controls today than several years ago, prices on such items as 
bananas, cocoa, coffee, and pharmaceuticals are still set by the government. Ecuador 
maintains a minimum wage policy.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
There are large disparities of wealth in Ecuador that increase the chances that property may be 
redistributed to the poor. In addition, corruption plagues the legal framework, making it 
sometimes difficult to enforce property rights.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>    
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
The Superintendency of Companies, the Superintendency of Banks and Insurance Companies, 
and the Ecuadorian Standards Institute are the main regulatory bodies in Ecuador. 
Government corruption in these and other agencies causes them to enforce regulations 
haphazardly, which often becomes a burden for business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Because of Ecuador's bureaucratic inefficiency and corruption, many entrepreneurs resort to 
the black market. For example, almost 48 percent of the labor force in the city of Quito is 
supplied by the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.25</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 2.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  One exception is a 44 percent tax level on corporate income for oil companies.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
