<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Estonia</TITLE>
<H2>ESTONIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Of all the former Soviet republics, the Baltic country of Estonia has been the most 
successful in reforming its economy. The government has undertaken a massive privatization 
policy, selling off many formerly state-owned enterprises. It has established its own national 
currency_the kroon_which is stable and convertible. The inflation rate has fallen dramatically, 
while trade with the West has grown 500 percent since 1991.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of protection)</I><BR>
Estonia has an average tariff rate of approximately 4 percent. <FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>   Few, if any, non-tariff barriers to trade exist.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Estonia has a flat income tax rate of 26 percent. It has a top corporate tax rate of 26 percent. 
Estonia also has a 26 percent capital gains tax, an 18 percent value-added tax, a 20 percent 
social security tax, a 13 percent social insurance tax, and a 1 percent land tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Estonia's government consumes 10.5 percent of GDP, which is low.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>  (High level of inflation)</I><BR>
While still relatively high, Estonia's inflation has dropped dramatically in the past two years. Its 
annual inflation rate was 1,009 percent in 1992. In 1993, it sank to about 26 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
There are relatively few restrictions on foreign investors. Investments are permitted in some 
utilities. All foreign investment ventures are treated the same as Estonian businesses. There 
are no repatriation requirements forcing investors to keep their capital in the country.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Banks in Estonia have been made more accessible to foreign operation. Private banks are 
growing and competition with state banks is increasing.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Price controls have been removed on 95 percent of Estonia's goods and services. Price controls 
remain only on such items as electricity and energy-producing agents like shale. There is a 
minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
The chances of expropriation in Estonia are low. Estonia's legal protection of private property is 
high.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation)</I><BR>
There are some regulations that pose a burden on business. For example, increased attention to 
health, safety, and the environment, as well as testing and standards, is posing a burden on 
some business creation. However, obtaining a business license is relatively easy and 
corruption-free.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Because of reduced barriers to trade and a limited regulatory environment, the black market is 
shrinking. Still, many services like taxis are supplied by the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.25</TH>  
    
Trade 1				Banking 2  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 1		Black Market 3 
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This rate was derived by taking Estonia's taxes raised from international trade in 1991 and 
determining its percentage of total imports. This probably understates the real average tariff rate.<BR>
[2]  This score is based on the 1993 inflation rate.
</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
