<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Ethiopia </TITLE>
<H2>ETHIOPIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Ethiopia was never colonized by a European power. Years of civil war and Marxist 
economic policies have devastated Ethiopia, the second most populous country in sub-Saharan 
Africa and one of its poorest. The Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Party seized 
power in 1991, having defeated the Marxist regime of Mengistu Haile Mariam. The transitional 
government of President Meles Zenawi is now attempting not only to overcome Mengistu's 
economic legacy, but to stop an ethnic-based secessionist movement in the Ogaden. Zenawi's 
government favors a mixed economy and enjoys considerable support from foreign aid donors. 
Ethiopia is confronting potential famine brought about by poor rains.  
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Although Ethiopia has liberalized trade somewhat, the average tariff rate remains a high 29 
percent. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Total Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Ethiopia has a 16-bracket income tax code with the highest rate pegged at 85 percent. <FONT 
SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>    The corporate tax rate in Ethiopia is 50 percent. Agricultural 
income is additionally taxed. <FONT SIZE="-2">[3]</FONT> 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Ethiopia's government consumes 14.8 percent of GDP, which is considerably lower than the 
26.6 percent figure for 1990. Ethiopia's industrial sector is dominated by 15 public 
enterprises. 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Very low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Ethiopia's inflation rate has been historically low. Its average annual rate of inflation from 1980 
through 1991 was only 2.4 percent. This was artificially low because Ethiopia was a 
communist country until 1991. Ethiopia's inflation rate has increased over the last few 
years, however, rising to around 10 percent. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Zenawi's regime has not done much to dismantle the hostile foreign investment climate created 
by the previous Marxist regime. Sectors off limits to private investment include the defense 
industry, large-scale electric power generation, postal, telecommunications, and major 
transportation services. The new government has been slow to authorize new foreign 
investments. Ethiopians are granted priority for investment opportunities. A heavy 
regulatory burden also discourages foreign investment. Nevertheless, foreign investors can 
enjoy some tax incentives.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
The financial sector, previously an exclusive domain of the state, was recently liberalized. 
Private investment in banking and insurance is now permitted. The dominant Commercial 
Bank of Ethiopia and the Ethiopian Insurance Corporation, however, will remain under full 
state ownership; private investment is limited to newly established bank and insurance 
operations. Banking and insurance ownership limits apply to individuals and families, and 
no foreign ownership of Ethiopian banks is permitted. Foreign banks may not operate in 
Ethiopia. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Ethiopia has recently liberalized prices. Private operators were permitted to compete with the 
state-run grain and coffee distribution networks, allowing for greater price and wage 
competition. State dominance of the industrial and transportation sectors reduces price 
competition. As with many African countries, only a small percentage of the work force in 
Ethiopia is employed for wages. There is no minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
The Mengistu regime nationalized most industries and vast tracts of agricultural land. The new 
government has decided that rural land will remain under state ownership. Urban land also 
will remain as property of the state, available to the private sector only through revocable 
long-term leases. Bureaucratic red tape and corruption further weaken property rights in 
Ethiopia. Property may be expropriated legally with compensation. 
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Impromptu police clearings of street stalls and other persecutions of merchants who threaten 
politically favored businesses are commonplace. The business permit system is used to 
favor certain ethnic groups and is subject to corruption. Businesses targeted for government 
crack-downs include schools for teaching computer skills, foreign languages, and typing. 
Ethiopia's regulatory regime greatly impedes legitimate business activity. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Many legitimate economic activities, particularly retailing, are driven underground by repressive 
authorities. Considerable smuggling exists in the sale of coffee. Corruption is a major 
problem in Ethiopia.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.80</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 5		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>


<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Source: United States Department of State, Bureau of African Affairs, Office of Economic 
Policy.<BR>
[2]  Ethiopia's income tax score is based solely on its maximum bracket.<BR>
[3]  Tax information from Foreign Tax and Trade Briefs, Matthew Bender and Co., Inc., June 1994.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
