<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Fiji</TITLE>
<H2>FIJI</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	A small island nation in the South Pacific Ocean, Fiji gained its independence from the 
United Kingdom in 1970. It developed a democratic constitution shortly thereafter. However, 
during the 1980s several military coups occurred. Because of political instability, Fiji has been 
unable to adopt significant, long-lasting economic reform. As a result, sustainable economic growth 
has been unattainable.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Fiji has an average tariff rate of 16.2 percent. It has many non-tariff barriers. For example, 
special licenses are required for agricultural and consumer goods.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Fiji has a top income tax rate of 40 percent. The tax rate for the average income is 5 percent. 
Fiji has a top corporate income tax rate of 47.5 percent. It also has a 30 percent capital 
gains tax, a 10 percent value-added tax, and a 7 percent to 23 percent social contributions 
tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Fiji's government consumes 28.2 percent of the country's GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Fiji had an average annual inflation rate of 6.1 percent from 1980 to 1991. This rose to 
somewhat above 12 percent in 1992 and 1993.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Foreign investors are not permitted to buy into and gain a controlling share of any domestically 
owned business. There are many other restrictions on foreign investment in Fiji. For 
example, all investments must be approved by the government. But Fiji does conform to an 
established foreign investment code.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Fiji has restrictions on banking. The system is under the control of the government and 
competition is stifled through the strict control of interest rates. However, a private banking 
industry exists. There is little or no corruption.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Fiji maintains price controls on a select group of commodities and consumer goods. Fiji has a 
minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Property expropriation in Fiji remains a possibility. There is inadequate protection of property 
rights, and the dispute settlement process is not sufficient.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Fiji is a heavily regulated economy. Many regulations pose a significant burden on business. For 
example, the Prices and Incomes Board monitors businesses in their pricing and wage 
policies. If the government deems them to be contrary to its established policy, it may shut 
down the business if it fails to comply. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Fiji's relatively closed market for imports creates a substantial black market in smuggled items.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.30</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
