<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Gabon</TITLE>
<H2>GABON</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Central African country of Gabon gained its independence from France in 1960. With 
a population of only some 1 million people, and enjoying generous deposits of oil and other such 
valuable minerals as uranium and manganese, Gabon is one of the most prosperous countries in 
sub-Saharan Africa. Gabon is a member of the French Franc Zone and maintains close ties with its 
former colonizer. This relationship has provided Gabon with a measure of economic and political 
stability unusual in Africa. In 1990 French troops stationed in Gabon quelled riots against the regime 
of President Omar Bongo, who has been slowly making political and economic reforms. However, 
Bongo retains tight control over political activity. The Gabonese economy has been partially 
restructured under the guidance of the International Monetary Fund.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Gabon's average tariff rate is a high 30.7 percent. The tariff rate is particularly high on 
electronics, vehicles, and luxury goods. There are quantitative import restrictions on sugar, 
vegetable oil, soap, mineral water, and cement. Rice and wheat are subject to import 
licenses. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (Very high tax rates)</I><BR>
The highest tax bracket is 60 percent. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  The corporate tax 
rate in Gabon is 40 percent. Additionally, companies must pay 5 percent of pre-tax profits 
into the Gabonese Investment Fund. Small and medium businesses routinely receive tax 
holidays. Gabon also maintains a 40 percent capital gains tax, a goods and services tax 
ranging from 4 percent to 14 percent,  and various other business and consumer taxes.  
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 17 percent. Gabon's public sector remains 
bloated, despite retrenchment efforts. While some government-controlled enterprises have 
been liquidated, there has been little privatization in larger state-owned companies.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Gabon's average annual rate of inflation between 1980 and 1991 was 1.5 percent. Inflation was 
at 4 percent in 1993. Under the Franc Zone Mechanism, Gabon exercises only limited 
control over its monetary policies. Instead, the Bank of France exerts tight control over 
Gabon's money supply. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
A 1989 rewrite of the investment code liberalized conditions for foreign business. While 
government participation in investment is no longer required, all private companies 
established in Gabon must contribute 10 percent of their shares to the government. There 
are only minimal restrictions on foreign investors in most areas. The government has 
allowed foreign-owned operations to compete with local business. There are very few areas 
off limits to foreign investors, but the government dominates the most lucrative sectors of 
the marketplace. There are no free trade zones in Gabon, but tax holidays for certain 
investors are available. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR> 
<I>Score: Not Scored</I><FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT><BR>
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Price controls are imposed on 17 goods and on most services, including insurance and 
construction. A relatively high minimum wage has attracted many unskilled immigrants 
from neighboring African countries. The minimum wage for non-Gabonese is 80 percent of 
what Gabonese workers must be paid. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Foreign property is unlikely to be expropriated. However, there have been charges that 
government officials have used coercion to obtain control over successful businesses. 
Ethnic clashes over property occur. Great disparities of wealth increase the chances that 
property rights might not be adequately protected in the future. 
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
 While the bureaucracy is generally effective, lengthy delays in the processing of some business 
investments and expansions are common. Regulations have increasingly complicated the 
business environment. Moreover, the success of Gabonese enterprises depends largely 
upon their political connections. A 1992 "Gabonization" program forces employers to 
decrease the number of foreigners in their work force. The President has called upon 
foreign-owned businesses to hire more Gabonese workers. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The government's considerable control and influence over economic activity encourages black 
market activity. So, too, do the high tariffs on luxury goods and automobiles, which 
encourage smuggling.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.05</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking N/A  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Gabon's income tax score is based solely on its maximum bracket.<BR>
[2]  Information was not available for this factor.

</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
