<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Haiti</TITLE>
<H2>HAITI</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Caribbean nation of Haiti has little economic freedom. Although turning toward 
democracy in February 1991, freely elected President Jean-Bertrand Aristide is not an advocate of 
free markets. Following his ouster by military coup in September 1991, the country was isolated 
economically and remains one of the poorest countries in the world. Given Aristide's anti-market 
past, the newly returned president is unlikely to launch major economic reforms.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Although the economic embargo of Haiti has been lifted, few products can be easily imported. 
Crime, corruption, and poor infrastructure make the Haitian market inaccessible to most 
imports.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Haiti has a top income tax rate of 30 percent. Haiti's tax collection system is so poor that it is 
impossible to determine which rate applies to the average income. Tax evasion is massive. 
Direct taxes paid represent only 15 percent of total receipts. <FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>  Haiti has a top corporate income tax rate of 35 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The most recent reliable figures for Haiti's government consumption are for 1987. In that year, according 
to the World Bank, central government expenditure as a percentage of gross national product was 18.7 
percent. However, this figure probably seriously understates the government's true consumption of GNP. 
<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>
  Gross domestic product, for example, has shrunk every year since 1991. If estimated 
government expenditures remain relatively constant, Haiti's government consumption is 
estimated to be more than 25 percent of GDP. 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Haiti's average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 7.1 percent. However, in 1992 and 
1993, inflation approached 20 percent. Some estimates place the current inflation rate at 
closer to 35 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Sanctions prevented most, if not all, foreign investment in Haiti. But even under Aristide, 
foreign investment was not welcome. Haiti's hostility to foreign investment is likely to 
continue.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Although there are some foreign banks operating in Haiti, the system is collapsing under 
government intervention, strict control of credit, a loose monetary policy, and a corrupt, 
inefficient government bureaucracy.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4- (High level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Haiti has controlled prices on many items, including cement and gasoline. With most of its 
economy in shambles, the government has sought to control prices on a variety of basic 
staples such as certain foods. Haiti maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property has little or no protection in Haiti.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of regulation)</I><BR>
Corruption is rampant. It was virtually impossible to open a business legally under the military 
regime. Members of the military used regulations as a way to extort goods and services 
from businesses. They would, for example, use force to confiscate products directly from 
vendors. With Aristide, these practices are likely to end. However, Haiti's bureaucracy still 
will be corrupt and will continue to pose a burden on business. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Even before the embargo, the government's price controls and other inefficient government 
policies created a large black market. At that time, the black market was around 40 percent 
of GDP. Today, the embargo has created a black market that surpasses GDP.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 4.20</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 5  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 4  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 5  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 5  
Foreign Investment 5		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  For this factor Haiti was graded only on the top income tax rate.<BR>
[2]  Government consumption as a percentage of GDP is not available.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
