<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Honduras</TITLE>
<H2>HONDURAS</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Honduras declared its independence from Spain in 1821 when it formed the Federal 
Republic of Central America with Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala, and Nicaragua. Honduras 
withdrew from that group of nations and declared independence in 1838. In the 1950s, the 
government introduced agrarian reforms such as returning many farms to private farmers. This 
became the basis for a market system. Military coups and civil unrest characterized the next several 
decades. Honduras has yet to establish a successful economic reform plan.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Honduras has tariffs ranging from 5 percent to 20 percent. It has an average tariff rate of about 
12 percent. It maintains non-tariff barriers through strict labeling requirements and has an 
effective ban on poultry and corn imports.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Honduras has a top income tax rate of 40 percent. There are no taxes imposed on average 
income. Honduras has a top corporate tax rate of 40 percent. Honduras also has a 40 
percent capital gains tax, a 7 percent sales tax, and local taxes.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Honduras's government consumption figure as percentage of GDP is 11.5 percent.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Honduras had an annual average rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 6.8 percent. In 1992, 
inflation went up to 8.4 percent. In 1993, the inflation rate reached 10 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Honduras maintains several restrictions on foreign investment. Special state authorization must 
be obtained for investments in the air transport, forestry, and telecommunications 
industries. The government also requires that a majority of certain companies must be 
owned by Hondurans. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Foreigners must obtain government permission for engaging in some types of banking services. 
Domestic banks are under the control of the government and the central bank.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
After years of eliminating price controls, Honduras in 1993 resorted to price controls on a 
basket of 44 goods, including certain foodstuffs. Honduras has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Expropriation in Honduras remains likely. The government does not fully protect property, and 
corruption exists. Moreover, the police's inability to deal with civil unrest poses a threat to 
property.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Honduras's bureaucracy suffers from corruption,  and cronyism. Regulations are posed 
unequally and often haphazardly. Regulations, therefore, remain a huge threat to business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Because Honduras maintains significant barriers to trade, the black market is rather large. 
Almost half of the labor force is supplied by the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.25</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
