<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Hungary</TITLE>
<H2>HUNGARY</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Once part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, Hungary established a communist system after World 
War II. The communist government, which had practiced a type of reform communism, collapsed in 1989 
and a democratically elected government introduced market reforms soon after. Despite the recent victory 
of socialists in the 1990 elections, Hungary's political climate is relatively stable. Hungary has an efficient 
intellectual property rights protection system, relatively weak labor unions, and a liberal foreign trade policy. 
Hungary has pursued an extensive privatization program. Still, the public sector produces about 60 percent 
of GDP.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Hungary has an average tariff rate of 12 percent. It also has a $750 million import quota that covers 
about 25 percent of all its imports. These quotas mainly affect such consumer products as 
automobiles, clothing, leather footwear, and foodstuffs.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)</I><BR>
Hungary has a top income tax rate of 44 percent. The average income level is taxed at 35 percent. 
Hungary has a top corporate income tax rate of 36 percent. Hungary also has a 36 percent capital 
gains tax, a 10 percent to 25 percent valued-added tax, and local taxes.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Hungary's government consumes 12.2 percent of GDP. This is up from about 10 percent in 1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of inflation)</I><BR>
The annual inflation rate in 1992 was 23 percent. In 1993 it was 15 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Hungary maintains few restrictions on foreign investment. Some tax holidays have been eliminated.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
The Hungarian banking system remains under government control. Competition is constrained through 
strict control of credit and interest rates.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Hungary has eliminated most price controls. It has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
There is little chance of property expropriation in Hungary. Private property is guaranteed. However, 
the legal system can be corrupt, ineffective, and inefficient.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation)</I><BR>
Hungary has few regulations that burden business. A business license is required for only a few 
activities. However, new consumer protection and environmental laws are becoming a burden to 
businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
A moderate black market still exists in Hungary, especially in transportation.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.80</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>


<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
