<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Ireland</TITLE>
<H2>IRELAND</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Ireland is predominantly a free market. Throughout most of its history Ireland was an 
agricultural country. Since the mid-1950s, however, Ireland has become increasingly industrialized. 
Today, mining, manufacturing, construction, and public utilities account for about 37 percent of 
gross domestic product. Agriculture accounts for only 12 percent of GDP. In the late 1980s and 
early 1990s, Ireland became a base for production of advanced consumer electronics products. 
Many high-tech companies, both foreign and domestic, have opened shop there.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif"> 
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
As part of the European Union, Ireland has an average tariff rate of 3.6 percent. However, 
Ireland maintains some of the strictest plant and animal health standards in the European 
Union. These often work as barriers to imports for items like meat and vegetables.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Ireland has a top income tax rate of 48 percent. The average income level is taxed at 27 
percent. Ireland has a top corporate income tax rate of 40 percent. It also has a 40 percent 
capital gains tax and a 21 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Ireland's government consumes about 16 percent of gross domestic product. The government 
has sold most state-owned industries. There are no prohibitions on private sector 
involvement in any sector of the economy. State-owned industries are confined to such 
areas as the production of energy and the telecommunications industry.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Ireland had an average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 5.8 percent. Inflation was 
around 3 percent for 1993 and 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Ireland welcomes foreign investment and offers such incentives as a guaranteed 10 percent 
maximum tax on investment profits for manufacturing companies. However, foreigners 
may not invest in sugar production, the production of electricity, or air and rail transport 
companies.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Ireland has a highly competitive and advanced banking and financial system. Foreign banks are 
welcome in Ireland and treated equally with domestic banks.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
There are no price controls in Ireland. It does maintain a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property expropriation is very unlikely. Property receives sufficient protection from the court 
system.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Regulations are applied uniformly and are not a substantial burden to business. However, 
regulations in Ireland have been increasing. The environmental movement is putting a great 
strain on businesses, especially on manufacturing companies which must comply with 
stringent air quality laws. New occupational health and safety laws also pose a burden to 
some businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Ireland has a moderate black market. Because of the conflict in Northern Ireland, an entire 
smuggling network was established to run guns and weapons to the Irish Republican Army. 
This network has grown over the years to include stolen items ranging from consumer 
electronics, like computers, to cigarettes and cigars.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.20</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 2  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>


<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
