<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Israel</TITLE>
<H2>ISRAEL</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Israel receives the largest amount of America's foreign aid. In late 1986 it formed a free 
trade area with the U.S. which has increased trade between the two countries. But despite the free 
trade agreement and the massive infusions of foreign aid, Israel's economy is mixed.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif"> 
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Israel has an average tariff rate of 2.3 percent. However, this figure severely understates 
Israel's trade protectionism. Many imports from America come in at reduced rates because 
of the free trade area. However, duties applied to less developed countries and others can 
be as high as 95 percent. In addition, Israel imposes such non-tariff  barriers as import 
bans, strict product standards, and import quotas.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)</I><BR>
Israel has a top income tax level of 50 percent. The average income level is assessed a 20 
percent tax. Israel has a top corporate tax rate of over 45 percent. Israel also maintains a 10 
percent capital gains tax and a value-added tax of 17 percent.  
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Israel has a central government expenditure as a percentage of GDP of 52 percent. <FONT 
SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>    This high level of spending is mainly the result of military 
expenditures and social welfare programs.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
Israel had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 89 percent. In 1992 and 1993, 
inflation dropped to 15 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
There are no significant investment barriers to foreign investment in Israel. The government 
permits 100 percent foreign ownership of businesses. The government also employs such 
investment incentives as tax holidays.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Banks in Israel are highly centralized, and a significant portion of the industry is manipulated by 
the government through regulations and controls. Banks are restricted from investing in real 
estate, insurance, and some other business activities. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most price controls have been lifted. They remain on a few items. Israel has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Expropriation of property in Israel is unlikely. Israel has a sophisticated legal system that 
provides extensive protection of private property. However, civil unrest and political 
uncertainty raise the risk of confiscation.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation)</I><BR>
Despite the large central government role in the economy, Israel has an efficient bureaucracy 
which encourages business. Regulations are applied evenly and do not pose a significant 
burden on business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Israel's import barriers have created a fairly substantial smuggling business in consumer goods. 
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.10</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 3  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 1		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>



<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This figure is based on IMF figures for the most recent date, 1991.
</FONT>

