<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Italy</TITLE>
<H2>ITALY</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Italy is the fifth-largest economy in the world and is a member of the G-7 group of 
advanced industrialized nations. Despite its relatively large economy, Italy has pursued state-
interventionist economic policies that have created periods of deep economic recession and have 
restricted economic freedom. Today, however, Italy is making great strides in attacking its federal 
budget deficit, crime, and corruption and in removing the state from many economic activities. 
Under the leadership of Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi, Italy has paved a path of economic 
reform unlike any in this country for several decades. While Berlusconi is dedicated to free market 
reform, the entrenched bureaucracy may resist rapid changes.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">  

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
As a member of the European Union, Italy has an average tariff rate of 3.6 percent. However, 
Italy's customs procedures can sometimes be strict and arbitrary, particularly with respect 
to agricultural goods. This affects imports from all non-European Union countries.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5+ (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4+ (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5+ (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Italy has a top income tax rate of 51 percent. The average income level is taxed at a rate of 27 
percent. Italy has a top corporate income tax rate of 36 percent. <FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>   Italy also has a 36 percent capital gains tax and a 19 percent value-
added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Italy's government consumes about 17 percent of GDP. The government is responsible for 
about 40 percent of all economic output.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Italy's average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 9.5 percent. It fell to 4.7 percent in 
1992. Inflation is around 3.9 percent in 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
As part of the European Union, Italy generally welcomes foreign investment, mainly because of 
its importance in helping bring new technologies into Italy's ailing industries. There are, 
however, a few restrictions and bans on foreign investment in domestic air transport, 
aircraft manufacturing, and state monopolies. In addition, industrial projects require a 
multitude of approvals and permits. Still, overall barriers to foreign investment are low by 
global standards.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Many banks in Italy are state-owned. Banks face extensive government restrictions on selling 
real estate, investing in industries, and selling insurance and securities. Still, Italy has 
managed to eliminate most of the corruption in the banking industry. In a new sweeping 
banking reform measure that took effect in January 1994, the banking sector was opened to 
market forces for the first time in decades. As a result, private banks are growing in 
number, and the government plans eventually to privatize the remaining state-owned banks.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
While few direct government price controls exist, the government affects prices through some 
state-owned and subsidized industries whose pricing policies are not determined by market 
forces. Yet most prices are determined by the market. Italy has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is safe from arbitrary government expropriation. Many state-owned interests are being 
returned to the private sector, thus increasing opportunities for individuals to acquire 
property. Italy has an advanced legal system to protect property, although claims of 
corruption exist.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
While Italy's government regulations can be cumbersome and open to corruption, Prime 
Minister Berlusconi has made progress in reducing corruption in the bureaucracy. It is easy 
to open businesses, and bribes are no longer necessary. By global standards, regulations are 
low.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
While Italy's organized criminals are heavily involved in drugs and guns, black market activities 
in smuggling, transportation services, and the construction industries are relatively small. 
Moreover, Italy's government is making progress in stamping out some organized crime.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.50</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 3  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>


<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  It is important to point out that many Italians probably avoid paying taxes altogether.
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
