<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Japan</TITLE>
<H2>JAPAN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>


<P>	Japan has been one of the fastest-growing economies in the post-World War II era. 
With a democracy firmly in place by 1946 and an economy in ruins, Japan eliminated most 
elements of socialism and adopted the basics of a free market system which helped propel it to the 
economic status it now enjoys.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif"> 

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Many economists argue that Japan is very protectionist. Yet Japan's average tariff rate is 
among the lowest in the world, around 1.5 percent--less even than the U.S. Japan also has 
eliminated quotas in rice, something not even considered just a year ago, and has begun to 
open up its market. While tariffs have never really been the problem in Japan, like the U.S. 
and the European Union it remains plagued with non-tariff barriers. These include 
government red tape, government toleration of business collusion, exclusionary private 
business practices, a fragmented distribution system, and a relatively unapproachable 
government bureaucracy. While these often prove to be impediments to imports, Japan's 
market is more accessible than those of most countries in the world.
 <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  Therefore, by global standards, especially when compared to countries 
like Bangladesh, India, and Yemen, Japan's trade barriers are relatively low.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4+ (High tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5 (Very high tax rates)</I><BR>
Japan's top income tax rate is 50 percent. The tax rate that applies to the average income level 
is 20 percent. Japan is now considering an income tax reduction. Japan has a top marginal 
corporate tax rate of 37.5 percent. In addition, Japan has an inhabitant's tax that is paid to 
the prefecture or municipality in which the company is located, a capital gains tax of 37.5 
percent, and an enterprise tax of 6 percent to 12.84 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low government consumption)</I><BR>
Government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 9.4 percent.  The Japanese government 
has gone from periods of extensive subsidies to opening up its market for some products, 
such as rice. Moreover, Japanese government expenditures have been kept lower than 
those of other countries because the United States has provided for Japan's defense.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Japan's annual inflation rate averaged only 1.5 percent from 1980 to 1991. Inflation was 1.8 
percent in 1992. In 1993, Japan actually had a negative inflation rate of about 2 percent. So 
far in 1994, prices are still shrinking.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Japan's foreign investment procedures were overhauled in the early 1990s. However, Japan 
continues to maintain investment restrictions on agriculture, aircraft, atomic energy, 
fisheries, forestry, leather goods, oil and gas production, and space development. 
Moreover, Japan's close government relationship with private businesses often proves to be 
a barrier to foreign investment because some businesses and government agencies collude 
to make foreign investments too costly.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
The banking industry is very competitive in Japan. The government places few restrictions on 
Japanese banks and their ability to engage in a variety of services. For example, banks are 
allowed to underwrite, deal, and broker all kinds of securities through subsidiaries. This 
allows banks to be more competitive. Japan remains the world's largest net creditor. Some 
minor restrictions exist on foreign banks.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
There are no price controls in Japan except on rice. Wages are mainly set by the market. Japan 
has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high protection of private property)</I><BR>
Japan has an efficient legal and court system capable of protecting property rights. Government 
expropriation of property is unlikely.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation)</I><BR>
While Japan's economy often is characterized as heavily regulated, most businesses enjoy a 
large amount of economic freedom. The process for opening a business in Japan has been 
made easier in the last several years. Moreover, while some regulations may pose burdens 
directly on individuals, Japan's regulations on businesses are aimed at allowing them 
enough room to maximize profits. Therefore, many regulations on businesses either are not 
enforced or are not a significant burden on business. For example, Japan rarely enforces its 
anti-trust laws, allowing businesses to join forces without the threat of anti-monopoly 
litigation from competitors. Therefore, by global standards, Japan's level of regulation is 
low.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The Japanese government has undertaken an immense crackdown on such illegal activities as 
the buying and selling of guns and narcotics.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 1.95</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 2  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>


<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Using the criteria set forth in this Index, Japan's heavy use of non-tariff barriers moves its score 
one point higher, representing less economic freedom.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>



