<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Kenya</TITLE>
<H2>KENYA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The East African country of Kenya gained its independence from Great Britain in 1963. Its 
long period of one-party rule ended in 1991 with the legalization of opposition political parties. 
Political freedoms, however, remain fairly constricted. Its economy, once one of Africa's most free 
and prosperous, has deteriorated badly because of government corruption and mismanagement. 
Economic growth is negligible. Recent efforts at economic liberalization by the government of 
Daniel arap Moi have brought donors back to Kenya. The current government until recently had 
been all but cut off from foreign aid. Western donors were unhappy with Kenya's economic 
mismanagement.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Kenya's average tariff rate is high at 15.7 percent. Moreover, its customs system is prone to 
corruption. However, in 1993 import licenses were abolished for most goods.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score -  Income taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score -  Corporate taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3.5+ (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Kenya has a top income tax rate of 40 percent. The tax rate applicable to the average Kenyan 
taxpayer is approximately 13 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   Locally 
incorporated companies are taxed at 35 percent and branches of foreign companies at 42.5 
percent. Businesses operating within Export Processing Zones, which are areas in which 
businesses receive special tax incentives,  enjoy a ten-year tax holiday. Kenya also 
maintains a value-added tax with rates ranging from 18 percent to 40 percent. 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 9.3 percent. The government has plans to 
privatize many state-owned companies, though 33 will be kept in the hands of the state. To 
date, only 22 small companies have been privatized. 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Kenya's average annual rate of inflation between 1980 and 1991 was 9.2 percent. Inflation was 
40 percent for 1993. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Complete foreign ownership of Kenyan enterprises is permitted, although the government has a 
distinct preference for maintaining Kenyan participation. The government has suggested 
that foreigners would be acceptable buyers of state-owned enterprises slated for 
privatization.  Export Promotion Zones offering tax breaks have been established, but so far 
they have not been very successful in attracting foreign investors. Because investment 
proposals are approved on a case-by-case basis and the procedures for obtaining 
government approval of the investment is so  burdensome, arbitrary, and often corrupt, 
foreign investment in Kenya is declining.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The 1992 collapse of two Kenyan banks and the suspension of 12 other financial institutions 
have destabilized the country's banking system. This followed a 1991 scandal involving 
high-ranking politicians who had improperly used their influence to arrange a government 
bail-out of some private banks which had made bad loans. Several state-controlled banks 
make loans to state industries. Some foreign banks have purchased financial institutions in 
Kenya.  
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls have been lifted in every sector of the economy except petroleum and 
pharmaceuticals. However, most agricultural products must be sold through monopolistic 
government marketing boards. Monopolies, many of them government-sanctioned, control 
approximately half of the Kenyan market. This reduces price competition. Kenya has a 
minimum wage. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is constitutionally protected from compulsory state takeover. In the exceptional case 
of expropriation, compensation is given, albeit in local currency. Nevertheless, the 
government has been threatening to nationalize the tourist industry. Moreover, there have 
been instances of foreign investors being arbitrarily deported. The independence of the 
judiciary is questionable.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Companies are registered with relative ease. However, some companies have found their  
operating licenses arbitrarily suspended. Businesses are required by the government to file 
monthly reports on their activities.  Because of regulations it is difficult to terminate 
employees. The result is that companies often are over-staffed and payroll demands are 
excessively high.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>   
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The government's monopoly on agricultural distribution encourages illegal trading in foodstuffs. 
The heavy regulation placed on business also encourages "illegal" commerce in many 
items, including used automobiles.   
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.05</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Kenya's income tax scale is progressive, with income proportioned among the various escalating 
rates.  
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
