<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Mexico</TITLE>
<H2>MEXICO</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	After years of suffering from socialist economic policies and limited economic freedom, 
Mexico is well underway in liberalizing its market. As with many countries reforming their 
economies, many of the benefits of the free market are just beginning to take effect in Mexico. 
Moreover, Mexico's efforts to integrate its economy with that of the U.S. and Canada with the 
passage of the North American Free Trade Area agreement will liberalize the Mexican economy 
even more. However, despite the NAFTA, Mexico still imposes limits on economic freedom, 
especially in respect to non-NAFTA members. In addition, Mexico's political system has not been 
reformed as rapidly as its economy, although some progress has been made.  Government 
corruption continues, particularly in the form of bribes and kick-backs for government projects, and 
there is a large black market.  Nevertheless, the overall prognosis for Mexico is good.  The reforms 
are taking root and the political system, despite some recent assassinations of major political figures, 
is holding firm.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Mexico's average tariff rate is about 9.4 percent. Moreover, Mexico maintains import licenses 
for 198 different products, including beans, cars and trucks, corn, dairy products, firearms, 
and poultry. As a result of the NAFTA, Mexico's tariffs on U.S. goods will drop to 
insignificant levels, although barriers will remain for non-NAFTA members.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Mexico's top marginal tax rate is 35 percent. The tax that applies to the average income level is 
17 percent. Mexico has a top corporate tax rate of 35 percent. Corporate capital gains are 
also taxed at the corporate rate. Mexico has a value-added tax of 10 percent, a 34 percent 
capital gains tax, a state tax on salaries, and a resident tax. 
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Mexico's government consumption as a percentage of GDP figure is 9 percent. 
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
While Mexico has made great strides in containing inflation, it has had a poor history of doing 
so. Mexico's average inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 66.5 percent. However, as a 
result of imposing a tighter monetary policy, the inflation rate was running at below 10 
percent in 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Mexico has reformed its foreign investment code to attract more investors, allowing for more 
equal treatment for foreign and domestic firms. Moreover, the NAFTA will further open 
Mexico to foreign investors from the U.S. and Canada as it becomes an attractive place to 
establish businesses.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Mexico heavily restricts foreign participation in its banking industry. Foreigners are permitted to 
own only a minority number of shares in Mexico's financial services industry. Areas in 
which foreign participation is strictly regulated include banks, brokerages, and insurance 
companies. Foreigners are prohibited from engaging in foreign exchange and credit unions. 
Moreover, domestic banks are prohibited from investing in real estate and industrial firms. 
There is some corruption involved in the dispensing of loans to state-owned companies.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Mexico maintains a minimum wage with incremental cost of living increases. Prices are set by 
both the market and the government. Some goods affected by price controls are black and 
white television sets, beer, bleach, blenders, cigarettes, electric batteries, electric irons, gas 
stoves, light bulbs, note books, pencils, pens, razors, refrigerators, and toothpaste. 
However, the government plans to eliminate these and other price controls over time. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property is guaranteed by the Mexican constitution. As more state-owned property is 
privatized, private property will be increasingly protected by law. There is now little fear of 
expropriation under the current political system.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Opening a business remains a complicated task. Each business must obtain a license or some 
other form of certification from numerous government agencies, including the Public 
Registry of Commerce, the Bureau of Statistics, federal and local tax authorities, the 
Mexican Social Security Institute, and the National Housing Fund. In addition, some 
localities require each business to belong to a local chamber of commerce and trade 
association. Moreover, additional licenses may be required from the Ministry of Health and 
other agencies. Although Mexico is making attempts to end corruption, its current 
regulatory environment remains an obstacle to business creation.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Mexico has a thriving black market that extends beyond drugs, prostitution, and guns. In many 
Mexican cities, a black market in transportation services such as taxis and busing is 
rampant. Black market labor is often available to businesses wanting to skirt minimum 
wages laws. Some estimates peg black market labor in Mexico City at over 40 percent.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.05</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 4  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>


<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
