<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Moldova</TITLE>
<H2>MOLDOVA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Located in Eastern Europe, Moldova gained its independence from the Soviet Union in 
1991. Moldova was a large food producing region in the Soviet Union. Since independence the 
economy has shrunk, unemployment has grown, and inflation has skyrocketed. The government 
still plays a larger role in the economy than does the free market. As a result, entrepreneurship is 
stifled.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Moldova has an average tariff rate of around 33.7 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   
It maintains non-tariff barriers to trade in a variety of areas. It lacks a uniform code of 
commerce and a legal foundation for the operation of the market.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: N/A </I><FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT> <BR>
<I>Score - Corporate taxation: 5+ (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 5+ (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Moldova has a top income tax rate of 50 percent. Its top corporate tax rate can reach 100 
percent, depending on how the government interprets its ill-defined tax code. Attempts are 
being made, however, to bring corporate taxes down.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Moldova's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 18 percent. However, most of 
the economy is government-owned.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Moldova had an annual inflation rate of over 1,000 percent in 1992. Inflation has remained 
constant.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Very high barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Moldova maintains many restrictions on foreign investment in services and other industries. 
There is no enforceable commercial code and foreign investment code.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Moldova's banking system is controlled mainly by four state-owned banks. There is little 
opportunity for private banking. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most prices are now set by the market with the exception of bread and dairy products, which 
are controlled by the government. Moldova has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Moldova has passed laws guaranteeing private property, including land. However, enforcement 
remains insufficient. Expropriation remains possible. 
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Moldova is in the midst of establishing a regulatory regime that will stress environmental 
protection and consumer safety. Existing government regulations are applied haphazardly 
and pose a burden on business. However, state planning has been reduced.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Moldova has a massive black market. The still rather large state-owned sectors of the economy 
are often unable to meet consumer demand for basic goods and services.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 4.10</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 5  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This figure is based on tax revenues from duties (2.8 billion rubles) as a percentage of total 
imports (8.4 billion rubles) in 1991.<BR>
[2]  It was not possible to obtain current income tax information on Moldova. Therefore, it was graded 
strictly on corporate taxes.

</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
