<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Mozambique</TITLE>
<H2>MOZAMBIQUE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Located in Southern Africa, Mozambique is the poorest country in the world. Portuguese 
control led to the start of a conflict for independence in 1964. By 1974, Portugal was fighting 
independence movements in Angola and Guinea Bissau as well as Mozambique. In that year, 
Mozambique was granted independence. Two years later, Mozambique entered a bloody civil war 
that only recently was concluded. Having held multi-party elections, Mozambique is now attempting 
to build a democratic government. With such a history of bloodshed and civil unrest, there has been 
little opportunity to develop a free market. Mozambique remains one of the most economically 
repressive countries in the world.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Mozambique has tariff rates that range from 5 percent to 35 percent.<FONT SIZE="-
2">[1]</FONT>   It maintains imports licenses for all imports.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Mozambique has a flat income tax rate of 40 percent. Mozambique has a top corporate income 
tax rate of 45 percent. Mozambique also has a 45 percent capital gains tax and a 5 percent 
to 150 percent consumption tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Mozambique has a government consumption figure of 29.1 percent of GDP. Most of the 
economy is state-owned. The government is contemplating a massive privatization 
program.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Mozambique had an average inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 37.6 percent. Inflation was 35 
percent in 1993. 
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
While there is growing interest in Mozambique's location as a preferred destination for foreign 
investment, little has been done to adopt a foreign investment code. Mozambique's 
controlled market and corrupt bureaucracy make investment nearly impossible. However, 
the government is updating and revising these laws. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Mozambique's banking system is in a state of complete chaos. It is dominated by government 
interference, and strict control by the central bank is maintained. Until very recently, the 
central bank had served as the sole commercial bank. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Significant price controls exist. Controls are imposed on about 15 percent of the goods and 
services available in Mozambique. Mozambique has a minimum wage. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property is subject to government expropriation. Mozambique's court system is unable 
to protect private property. This should improve somewhat with the recent conclusion of 
Mozambique's civil war.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Mozambique's regulatory environment is severely influenced by bureaucratic corruption. The 
private business sector is small and must compete with state-owned industries that look on 
private business with hostility.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Mozambique is a center for drug trafficking and money laundering. International crime 
organizations use Mozambique as a clearinghouse for black market trade between Asia and 
Europe. The value of these activities more than surpasses the official market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 4.40</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 4  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Most of Mozambique's imports fall into categories with tariff rates between 10 percent and 35 
percent. Mozambique's average tariff probably is between 15 percent and 19 percent.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
