<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Nicaragua</TITLE>
<H2>NICARAGUA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Central American country of Nicaragua became an independent state in 1838. Under 
the rule of the Sandinistas, Nicaragua became a socialist economy in 1979. Despite infusions of 
foreign aid, Nicaragua's economy grew little. Nicaragua held a democratic election in 1990 in which 
the victor, Violeta Chamorro, promised economic reform. But little progress has been made. The 
Sandinistas, who hold key government posts in the military and police, have blocked reforms, 
especially the privatization of state-owned enterprises and other nationalized sectors of the 
economy.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
According to the U.S. Department of Commerce, the average nominal protection of goods in 
1992 was 15.3 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   Moreover, Nicaragua maintains 
a host of non-tariff barriers. These include licensing requirements, services and investment 
barriers, and cumbersome customs procedures.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR> 
Total Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Nicaragua has a top marginal income tax rate of 30 percent. The tax rate that applies to the 
average income level is zero percent. Nicaragua has a top corporate tax rate of 30 percent. 
It also has a general sales tax of 15 percent, a consumption tax, and a municipality tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Nicaragua's government consumes 19.1 percent of GDP. However, much of Nicaragua's 
economy remains state-owned.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Nicaragua had an annual average rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 583.7 percent. In 1992, 
inflation ran at a rate of 23.1 percent. In 1993, inflation reached 20 percent and remained 
about the same in 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
While Nicaragua has liberalized its foreign investment code to allow for 100 percent foreign 
ownership, many barriers still remain. Much of Nicaragua's economy remains state-owned, 
and foreign direct investment is not permitted. Some sectors remain off limits to all 
investment. Each investor must get permission from the government, which is corrupt and 
inefficient. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Laws exist that theoretically permit foreign banks to open branches in Nicaragua, but in practice 
few foreign banks have been able to overcome the many hurdles that stand in their way. 
Few banks try to enter Nicaragua because of these inefficiencies. Domestic banks have yet 
to fully break away from government manipulation and control.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Almost all price controls have been lifted. However, the government of Nicaragua still maintains 
a significant amount of control over many prices. The government has managed to resist 
further price controls, but the system still relies on government influence of prices. 
Nicaragua has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4- (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property is not safe in Nicaragua. Property can be confiscated by both armed criminals 
and corrupt local governments. The court system is ill-equipped to deal with claims of 
property confiscation, and local law enforcement remains inadequate
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Government regulation remains a serious problem in Nicaragua. Environmental impact studies 
are required of businesses and in some cases may prevent the expansion of an existing 
business or the formation of a new one. Regulations are applied haphazardly, and 
corruption remains a problem. These and other regulations pose an extreme burden on 
business. 
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Nicaragua has a large black market in goods, including pharmaceuticals and agricultural 
products. There is rampant piracy of goods from Canada, the U.S., and Latin America. 
With 40 percent unemployment rates, large numbers of people engage in black market 
activities.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.90</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]<I>  Nicaragua,</I> U.S. Department of Commerce, Country Economic Memorandum Report 
No.12066-NI, Washington, D.C., February 2, 1994.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
