<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Nigeria</TITLE>
<H2>NIGERIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The West African country of Nigeria gained independence from Britain in 1960. It is rich in 
natural resources, including oil, coal, natural gas, and fertile soil. It has the largest population in 
Africa. Nigeria is in political crisis, with its military regime resisting demands for democratic change. 
Its mixed economy has been in decline. Per capita income has fallen from $1,000 to less than $300 
in the last decade. Mismanagement and corruption have effectively derailed the government's 
economic reform program, which was established in 1986. 
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Despite recent reductions on many goods, the average import duty of about 20 percent is high. 
All goods are subject to additional administrative surcharges totaling 6 percent. Trade 
liberalization has stalled. In 1993 the importation of 22 different items was banned. 
Included in these were textiles and agricultural products.  
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
The top income tax rate is 35 percent. The average taxpayer is in the 10 percent bracket. In 
1992 the corporate tax rate was lowered from 40 percent to 35 percent. In 1994 a 5 
percent value-added tax was introduced, applicable to 17 categories of goods and 24 
services.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>   
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Nigeria's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 6.4 percent. While the 
government has sold 86 state-owned enterprises to private owners, privatization has shown 
signs of stalling. Government-controlled companies, many of which are unprofitable, 
dominate many basic manufacturing industries. 
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of inflation) </I><BR>
Nigeria's average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 18.1 percent. Inflation was 45 
percent for 1993. For 1994, it is about the same.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Forty business categories are off limits to foreign investors. One hundred percent foreign equity 
is prohibited in commercial transport and most wholesale and retail trade industries. The 
ministry charged with approving foreign investment often acts arbitrarily. Special export-
processing zones, where firms enjoy duty-free importation of raw materials and export duty 
exemptions, have been established.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The number of commercial, mortgage, and merchant banks operating in Nigeria has been 
increasing. More than 100 domestic and foreign banks now operate branches in Nigeria. 
However, licensing refusals are common. Sixty percent Nigerian ownership is required in 
foreign ventures. The Nigerian central bank heavily regulates and controls banks. It fixes 
the discount rate and mandates lending to the agricultural and manufacturing sectors.  
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls were abolished in 1987. Six government marketing boards recently have been 
dismantled. However, price controls may return. A minimum wage has failed to keep pace 
with inflation. Wages are subject to negotiation between employers and unions, though the 
government has the final word on wage increases. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
There is a strong resistance to privatization efforts among labor unions. Property remains at risk 
from government expropriation. Enforcement of laws protecting property remains lax. 
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
The process for establishing a business has recently been streamlined. Problems remain, 
however. Foreign investors must deal with bureaucratic delays, entrenched corruption, and 
a complex web of restrictions and regulations.   
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
High tariffs and bans on textile and agricultural imports provide incentives for smuggling in 
Nigeria.  Government monopolies on sugar and fertilizer distribution also encourage illegal 
trade. A high duty on cigarettes and luxury goods makes smuggling in these areas very 
lucrative.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.15</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
