<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Oman</TITLE>
<H2>OMAN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Oman is located on the Arabian Peninsula, on the border of Saudi Arabia. Its coastal 
regions were conquered by the Portuguese in 1507 when the first traders arrived. The Portuguese 
were kicked out in 1650. For the next several centuries, Oman experienced political unrest.  In the 
19th century, Oman's ruling Sultans cultivated close relations with Great Britain to offset outside 
Arab and Persian interference in Oman's internal affairs. Today, Oman is an absolute monarchy. 
Oman's economy is heavily reliant on oil exports. It was not until 1991 that Oman began to 
introduce free market reforms.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Oman has an average tariff rate of about 6 percent. It has a flat 5 percent tariff rate and higher 
rates for alcohol and tobacco. Non-tariff barriers take the form of import licenses, which 
are required for all imports.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 1-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR> 
Total Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Income taxes are not imposed on individuals. Oman has a top corporate tax rate of 50 percent. 
<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  It also has a 50 percent capital gains tax, a training levy 
taken from non-Omani employees, and a social contributions tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Oman's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 43.5 percent.
<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT> 
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Oman had an average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of minus 3.1 percent. Inflation 
was around minus 5 percent in 1993. It remained constant in 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
With few exceptions, companies in Oman must be fully owned by Omanis. Foreign investment 
is allowed only through joint ventures and joint-stock companies. There are tax some 
incentives for investments.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Oman has a thriving banking sector with foreign participation and competitive Omani banks. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Oman has a minimum wage law. While few official price controls exist, the government is the 
main consumer of Omani goods and services. Therefore, prices are affected by government 
purchases.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property expropriation is possible, but not likely. Although Oman's court system is efficient and 
private property is well protected, property does not always receive total legal protection.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>   
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Oman has relatively straightforward regulations that are applied consistently in most cases.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Oman has a negligible black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.65</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 2  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This tax rate is for foreign-owned corporations.<BR>
[2]  This tax rate is derived from calculating central government expenditures as a percentage of GDP. 
The data come from the IMF.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
