<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Pakistan</TITLE>
<H2>PAKISTAN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The South Asian country of Pakistan gained independence following the partition of the 
Indian subcontinent and the end of British rule in 1947. Since then the country has remained poor 
and a huge recipient of foreign aid. Much of this aid has been squandered in economically useless 
projects, and Pakistan has been unwilling to adopt significant economic reforms. However, in 1994 
the government began to show signs of interest in free market reforms. For example, privatization 
of state-owned businesses is a new priority.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Pakistan has an average tariff rate of 26.3 percent. It maintains non-tariff barriers in the form of 
import licenses and fees.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Pakistan has a top income tax of 35 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>  Pakistan has a 
top corporate income tax rate of 52 percent. It also maintains a 49 percent capital gains tax, 
a sales tax, state and local taxes, and a capital value tax added to certain properties like 
factories and automobiles.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Pakistan's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 13.8 percent, which is up from 
11 percent in 1980.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Pakistan had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of  7 percent. It rose to 9.1 
percent in 1992 and to about 10 percent in 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
There are no restrictions on the amount of foreign investment in Pakistani industries. The 
government offers some incentives to foreign investors, such as certain types of tax 
incentives for specific investments.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks are becoming more accessible to foreigners. Local banks are permitted to engage in 
securities and investments, but not in insurance and real estate ventures. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Pakistan maintains price controls on many products. These prices are generally set on products 
such as automobiles that are manufactured by state-operated firms. Pakistan has a 
minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is protected in most cases and expropriation is unlikely. However, courts do not 
always enforce property rights.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Pakistan's economy is heavily regulated with substantial burdens on business. For example, 
Pakistan uses such laws as the 1983 Environmental Protection Ordinance, the Industrial 
Relations Ordinance of 1974 and the Factories Act that often burden Pakistani businesses. 
Some corruption exists.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Many consumer goods have extremely high tariffs, which encourages smuggling. Thus Pakistan 
has a substantial black market in such items as consumer electronics and recorded music.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.15</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 2  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  It was not possible to determine the tax on the average income level. Therefore, Pakistan has 
been graded on its top marginal rate alone.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
