<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Panama</TITLE>
<H2>PANAMA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Panama gained its independence from Spain in 1821 and from Colombia in 1903. Panama, 
of course, is the site of the U.S.-built Panama Canal. It held democratic elections on May 8, 1994. 
President Ernesto Perez Balladares advocates a strong policy of economic liberalization.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Panama's average tariff rate is 10.3 percent. Panama maintains significant non-tariff barriers, 
especially on agricultural imports. Panama, in fact, imposes import quotas on 48 agricultural 
products. Products like beef, corn, dairy, and soybeans are highly protected. 
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Panama has a top marginal tax rate of 30 percent. The tax rate that applies to the average 
income level is zero percent. Panama's top corporate tax rate is 35 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Panama's government consumption as percentage of GDP is about 22 percent. This is up from 
19 percent since 1980.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 4- (High level of inflation) </I><BR>
Panama had an average annual inflation rate of 25 percent between 1980 and 1991. Inflation 
increased to 29 percent in 1992 and has remained constant in 1993 and 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Most sectors of the Panamanian economy are open to foreign investment. There are only a few 
restrictions on sectors deemed "national interest" industries. For example, the mining 
industry may not be bought by foreign investors.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Domestic competition in banking is relatively high. Major banks from all over the world operate 
in Panama. Domestic banks may sell securities and real estate, and make some 
investments, but cannot sell insurance. There are few restrictions on opening banks in 
Panama.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most prices and wages are set by the market. However, the government maintains price 
controls on petroleum products, a few basic foodstuffs, industrial products, medicines, 
public transportation, and rent. Panama also imposes minimum wages.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property rights are constitutionally protected. However, the Panamanian legal system is not 
always able to deal with threats to property rights. Moreover, the privatization of state-
owned industries has slowed, and expropriation remains a possibility.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Opening a business in Panama is relatively easy. It requires obtaining a license from the 
Ministry of Commerce and Industry. However, bureaucratic red tape, mainly the result of 
corruption, remains a burden for many businesses.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR>
There is a large black market in illegal banking activities. Still, Panama's recent moves toward 
more economic liberalization have reduced the overall size of the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.70</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 1  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
