<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Paraguay </TITLE>
<H2>PARAGUAY</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The South American country of Paraguay gained independence from Spain in 1811. It had 
its first free democratic election in May 1993. The current government of Juan Carlos Wasmonsy is 
attempting to control government spending, reduce customs duties and inflation, and attract foreign 
investment. Recent economic liberalization policies have pushed Paraguay ahead of many of its 
neighbors in Latin America. Still, Paraguay remains plagued by corruption and a police force that is 
repressive.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Paraguay has an average tariff rate of 13.3 percent. Paraguay has no major non-tariff barriers. 
However, there are some barriers to some agricultural imports, such as poultry.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 2.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
There are no taxes on income derived from personal work, services provided, or professional 
services rendered. However, the top corporate tax rate is 30 percent. Paraguay also has a 
capital gains tax of 30 percent and a value-added tax of 10 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Government consumption of GDP is almost 9 percent, up from 6 percent in 1990.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of inflation) </I><BR>
Paraguay had an average annual rate of inflation of 25 percent from 1980 to 1992. Inflation 
was reduced to 18 percent in 1993.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
There are few restrictions on foreign investment in Paraguay. Some exceptions include 
complete investment restrictions in the cement industry and such public utilities as 
electricity, telephones, and water. There is a 95 percent corporate income tax exemption for 
five years following most investments. Moreover, the tax rate is fixed at 10 percent on 
reinvested profits, instead of the usual corporate tax rate of 30 percent.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Of the 24 commercial banks in Paraguay, 12 are domestic and 12 are branches of foreign 
banks.  Banks may engage in most financial activities, including the selling of stocks, bonds, 
and other securities.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls exist on bread, gasoline, and sugar. Paraguay has a minimum wage. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Expropriation of private property is a possible threat in Paraguay. Legal institutions are 
sometimes corrupt, resulting in insufficient protection of property rights.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Paraguay's government owns and operates several industries, including public utilities and those 
industries involved in the manufacture of cement and steel. These industries are highly 
regulated by government officials who oversee production levels and pricing. Moreover, 
additional environmental, consumer, labor, financial, and other regulations pose a burden to 
business. Obtaining a business license, however, is relatively easy.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Although most import restrictions have been removed, smugglers have a lucrative business 
bringing in illegal agricultural goods and products.  As much as 57 percent of Paraguay's 
labor force is supplied by the black market in Asuncion.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.75</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 2  
Taxation 2.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 1		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
