<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Peru</TITLE>
<H2>PERU</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The South American country of Peru gained its independence from Spain in 1879. Since 
then Peru was ruled by many different military governments. During the 1980s, Peru was among 
the most socialist and inefficient economies in the world. However, the 1990 election of Alberto 
Fujimori as president resulted in a wave of economic reforms. While far from achieving full 
liberalization, Peru has made great strides toward a free market.  Despite some progress in taming 
the Shining Path terrorists, Peru remains plagued by government corruption, civil unrest, and 
political violence.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Peru's average tariff rate is 17 percent. Plans exist to introduce a 15 percent flat rate in 1995. 
Peru maintains non-tariff barriers, principally with surcharges on agricultural goods, to 
offset the advantages enjoyed by other countries which subsidize agricultural production.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Total Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Peru has a top income tax rate of 30 percent. The tax rate that applies to the average income is 
15 percent. Peru has a flat corporate tax rate of 30 percent. In addition, it has a 30 percent 
capital gains tax and a sales tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Peru has an extremely low government consumption level. This, however, is more the result of 
inefficient government information than of low levels of government spending. According 
to the World Bank, the government of Peru consumes only 5.1 percent of GDP. This 
figure severely understates government consumption in Peru. It is probably the result of 
poor record keeping. More informal estimates place Peru's government consumption at 
around 12 percent of GDP. Finally, Peru still maintains a large state-owned sector.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Peru's average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 287.3 percent. That figure 
dropped dramatically to 73.5 percent in 1992 and about 40 percent in 1993.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
The government of Peru places restrictions on foreign investments in the transportation, 
financial services, news media, insurance, and utilities industries. Few restrictions exist in 
any other areas.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
There are few restrictions on foreign banks in Peru. Moreover, all banks may engage in selling 
securities, real estate, and insurance policies and may make some investments. Still, all 
banks are restricted in making investments in industrial firms. In addition, Peru's inefficient 
bureaucracy often makes it difficult to open new domestic banks.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. Peru maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Peru's legal system does not adequately protect private property because the court system is 
corrupt and it is difficult to get a fair hearing. Terrorism and violence are a severe threat to 
private property.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>    
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Peru remains a highly regulated economy. It is plagued by a corrupt and inefficient 
bureaucracy. Obtaining a business license, while made easier in recent years, may still 
require bribes and can take a great deal of time to complete. Environmental regulations, 
which have only recently been imposed, are a tremendous burden on business. 
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Peru has an extremely large black market. Besides a large underground economy in illegal 
drugs, many services like transportation and electricity are supplied on the black market. 
Moreover, almost 60 percent of the labor in Lima is now supplied by the black market, 
although this very high level is dropping because of free market reforms.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.40</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 2  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
