<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>The Philippines</TITLE>
<H2>THE PHILIPPINES</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	In 1900, the Philippines became a colony of the U.S. The Japanese conquered the 
Philippines during World War II and remained in control until driven off by U.S. forces in 1945. 
The many battles fought in the Philippines caused great structural damage, and much of the 
infrastructure was destroyed. On July 4, 1946, the Philippines became the independent Republic of 
the Philippines. The U.S. played a major role in the reconstruction of the Philippines after the end 
of World War II. However, between 1945 and 1953, the government's socialist economic policies 
prevented the country from establishing a free market economy. Successive administrations were 
plagued by ineffectiveness and corruption. The Philippines remains impoverished today, but market 
reforms are being implemented.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
The Philippines has an average tariff rate of 21.5 percent. Non-tariff barriers include import 
controls, licensing requirements, and strict labeling requirements.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR> 
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3 (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
The Philippines has a top income tax rate of 35 percent. The rate that applies to the average 
income level is 9 percent. The Philippines has a top corporate tax of 35 percent. It also has 
a 35 percent capital gains tax and a 10 percent value-added tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
The Philippines' government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 19.3 percent.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3 (Moderate levels of inflation) </I><BR>
The Philippines had an average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 14.6 percent. This 
decreased to about 7.8 percent in 1993.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
The Philippines has a moderate level of barriers to foreign investment. For example, foreigners 
may not invest in advertising, the mass media, public utilities, professional services, retail 
trade, and other areas.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The Philippine banking industry is controlled by the government. All banks must gain 
permission from the central bank to do business, which stifles competition. Foreign 
participation is limited to 30 percent of the voting stock of any given bank. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. The Philippines has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
The expropriation of private property is possible. The main reason for this is unstable economic 
conditions that may increase pressure on the government to nationalize industry.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
The Philippines has eliminated some regulations that pose significant burdens on business. Yet 
its regulatory regime is inconsistent, and regulations are applied haphazardly. The result is a 
high level of burden for businesses.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The Philippines has a large black market in international trade. Because of high levels of 
protectionism, there is smuggling of many items, including foodstuffs. Moreover, many 
citizens provide their labor on the black market to avoid paying taxes.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.30</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>


</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B26-305</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000618-B012-16</DOCOLDNO>
