<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Portugal</TITLE>
<H2>PORTUGAL</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Although the Portuguese economy grew at an average annual rate of 5.3 percent from 1965 
to 1980, it collapsed in the 1980s because of socialist economic policies. The revised Portuguese 
Constitution of 1982 called for the public ownership of land, natural resources, and the principal 
means of production. Today, Portugal still is burdened by a cumbersome bureaucracy.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
As part of the European Union, Portugal has a average tariff rate of 3.6 percent. However, it 
maintains non-tariff barriers by using quantitative import restrictions on foreign 
automobiles, fabrics, fuses, parts of footwear, iron and steel tubes and pipes, and weaving 
machines.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR> 
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Portugal has a top income tax rate of 40 percent. The rate that applies to the average income 
level is 25 percent. Portugal has a top corporate tax rate of 36 percent. In addition, Portugal 
has a 36 percent capital gains tax, a value-added tax ranging from 4 percent to 30 percent, a 
20 percent real estate tax, and a 50 percent inheritance tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The Portuguese government consumes 21 percent of GDP. Although the government has 
begun an ambitious privatization program, it still maintains major stakes not only in the 
banking industry, but in the production of alcohol, cement, chemicals, food, glass, and 
electricity.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Portugal had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 17.4 percent. In 1992, 
inflation was 12.6 percent, 7 percent in 1993 and 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Portugal has opened most of its industries to foreign investment. As a member of the European 
Union, Portugal treats all foreign companies equally with domestic companies. However, 
foreign investments are not permitted in postal carriers or in such public utilities as sewage 
treatment, transportation, and water services. While the European Union has reformed 
investment procedures, individual countries may have higher barriers to non-members. 
Such a case exists in Portugal with regard to local content requirements. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The government is 100 percent owner of some of Portugal's large banks, including the Caixa 
Geral de Deposito, and the Banco Fomento Exterior SA. This allows the government to 
play a large role in controlling the lending practices of private banks. Since the government 
subsidizes the state-owned banks, they get an unfair competitive advantage against private 
banks.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
The government eliminated almost all price controls in 1993. However, price controls remain 
on electricity, water, and pharmaceutical products. Portugal has a minimum wage. 
 <P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Portugal is privatizing much of its bloated state-owned sector. Citizens are increasing their 
purchases of shares in state-owned companies. This is providing an expanding base of 
private property.  Portugal has a relatively efficient legal system that adequately protects 
property in most cases. Expropriation is unlikely.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
Despite some liberalization, Portugal still maintains some significant regulations. One specific 
example is the 1987 environmental protection law that is the most stringent in the European 
Union. As a result of this law, new businesses and proposed business expansion projects 
must undergo very cumbersome environmental impact reviews by various government 
bureaucracies. This law often proves to be too high a hurdle for some businesses to jump. 
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Portugal's black market consists of selling such scarce goods as auto parts and pharmaceutical 
products. These scarcities are created by government-imposed price controls and trade 
quotas.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.80</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 3  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
