<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Romania</TITLE>
<H2>ROMANIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Romania's transition to democracy and free markets has been troubled and at times even 
violent. After the killing of former communist strongman Nicolae Ceausescu in 1989, Romania was 
ruled by former communists who were only lukewarm about democracy and free markets.  
However, the current government of Ion Iliescu has established an economic reform plan that, if 
implemented, could bring significant economic growth. Chief among these reforms, tax reductions 
and mass privatization are aimed at increasing economic output. However, political events may 
jeopardize economic reform. 
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Romania has an average tariff rate of about 3 percent. According to the U.S. State Department, 
"There are no known laws that directly prejudice foreign trade or business operations [in 
Romania]."<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR> 
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable  (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Romania has a top income tax level of 60 percent. The tax rate that applies to the average 
income is 40 percent. Romania has a top corporate income tax level of 40 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic 
Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Romania's rate of government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 35.5 percent. The 
public sector of the economy produces over 75 percent of GDP. Romania's government 
spending continues to outpace economic growth.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Communist control of the economy kept the official inflation rate artificially below what it 
should have been. Romania had an official average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 
1991 of 6.2 percent. However, this severely understates the real inflation rate for that 
period. Today, it is around 210.3 percent per year.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Romania maintains a fairly free market in foreign investment. Most barriers to foreign 
investment are informal, i.e., the result of bureaucratic red tape and inefficiency.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Romania's banking environment has yet to mature. Banks are under strict control of the 
government. There is little competition and few opportunities for foreign banks to operate 
inside Romania. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Prices are set mainly by the market. Exceptions include pharmaceutical products, public 
transportation services, and residential heat and energy supply. Romania has minimum 
wage laws. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (Low level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Romania has yet to establish a system of property protection. The legal system remains unable 
to arbitrate property rights disputes. Chances of expropriation, however, remain unlikely 
due to the government's massive privatization plans and growing free enterprise. For 
example, since 1990, the government has registered over 24,849 commercial companies 
that have foreign participation. This indicates that the private sector is growing.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation) </I><BR>
Regulations in Romania remain subject to haphazard application. This proves to be a significant 
barrier to business. Corruption is a problem for many businesses. 
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Most of Romania's economic activity is still performed in the black market. This is because a 
lagging economy has yet to provide many of the basic needs of consumers. Many food 
items, for example, can still be bought on the black market but are scarce at stores.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.55</TH>  
    
Trade 1				Banking 3  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Country Reports on Economic Policy and Trade Practices, p. 251.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
