<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Russia</TITLE>
<H2>RUSSIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The largest of the former Soviet republics, Russia has struggled for several years to introduce 
democratic political institutions and a free market economy. Progress has been slow. The government has 
given economic changes a back seat to political reforms. The result has been economic stagnation, civil 
unrest, coup attempts, and political polarization.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4- (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Russia's tariff ranges from 5 percent to 30 percent. Tariffs on luxury items can be significantly higher: 
as much as 150 percent. Russia's average tariff rate is about 14 percent. However, duty rates 
change rapidly and arbitrarily. Moreover, Russia maintains many trade restrictions left over from 
the Soviet regime. For example, safety standards, licensing and testing, and other requirements pose 
a significant non-tariff barrier. Corruption is present in the customs services, and bribes are 
sometimes necessary to bring goods into the country.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR>
Russia has a top income tax rate of 30 percent. The tax rate that applies to the average income level is 
12 percent. Russia has a top corporate income tax rate of 38 percent. This amount includes federal 
and regional taxes. Moreover, Russia has a 35 percent capital gains tax, a 20 percent value-added 
tax, a tax ranging from 85 percent to 100 percent on foreign profits, and a social payments tax. 
Because taxes are so high and arbitrary, tax evasion is widespread.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Russia's government officially consumes 22.7 percent of GDP. However, state-owned enterprises still 
account for a majority of industrial production. Thus, the government consumption figure is 
misleading. Russia's government probably consumes 26 percent to 35 percent of GDP.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Russia had an annual inflation rate of over 1,300 percent in 1992. It was 800 percent in 1993. Inflation 
ran at about 156 percent for most of 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
A 1991 Russian law permits foreigners to acquire newly privatized firms in Russia. Few legal restrictions 
exist on foreign investment. The only exceptions are investments in securities and insurance firms. 
However, the biggest barriers to foreign investment are the uncertainty of laws, crime, and political 
instability.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Many state-owned banks have been privatized. There is fierce competition in the commercial banking 
market. Foreign banks are now operating in Russia. However, Russia has yet to create a stable 
banking environment. A November 1993 presidential decree froze registered foreign bank activity 
and bars new foreign banks from entering Russia with less than 30 percent Russian ownership. This 
conflicts with a September 1993 decree sheltering foreign investors from adverse changes for three 
years. The entire banking system remains tightly controlled by the central bank. Moreover, most 
banks in Russia offer only a few services and are not as competitive as banks in the West. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Some 90 percent of all prices are set by free enterprise, while 5 percent are fixed by the state and 
another 5 percent are subject to government limits on the amount of profitability. However, because 
the government controls much of the economy through ownership of the public sector, it maintains 
a high level of indirect control over wages and prices. Russia maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
While private property is guaranteed in Russia, protection remains significantly lacking. The Russian 
court system works poorly; no clear and concise method of settling disputes of property has been 
developed. Moreover, protection of private property receives varying levels of police attention in 
different localities. Finally, corruption and organized crime remain a significant threat to private 
property. Expropriation remains possible due to unstable economic and political conditions.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Russia is experiencing a wave of dynamic entrepreneurial spirit. Many small businesses are growing 
around the larger cities. Small businesses are sprouting up by the hundreds in cities like Moscow. 
These businesses are easy to establish, and little regulation is imposed on them. However, the 
Russian government has yet to extend this "hands off" attitude to larger enterprises. Some 
regulations are arbitrary and unevenly enforced, posing a burden to business.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Russia's black market is massive. Despite recent moves to establish a free market, there are many black 
marketeers. Russia's black market is about the size of the legal market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.40</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
