<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Republic of China (Taiwan)</TITLE>
<H2>REPUBLIC OF CHINA (TAIWAN)</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Republic of China on Taiwan has become one of the fastest-growing economies in the 
world. In the late 1950s, Taiwan was mired in conflict with mainland China and suffering from an 
inefficient and overregulated economy. However, Taipei began to reform its economy in the late 
1960s. It guaranteed private property, set up a legal system to protect it, reformed its banks and 
financial sectors, stabilized taxes, gave away public lands to private individuals, and allowed the free 
market to expand. These policies have launched Taiwan, as one of Asia's famous "tigers," into the 
industrialized world.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   Today the ROC has annual rates of 
growth at around 6 percent.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Taiwan's average tariff rate is 4.9 percent, which is low.  However, Taiwan maintains rather 
high barriers to the importation of agricultural goods like chicken, meat, peanuts, and pork. 
Tariffs on these goods can be as high as 50 percent. Moreover, Taiwan's rather inefficient 
distribution system adds to the price of many products, making imported ones 
uncompetitive.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>  
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation:  2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 2.5-Stable (Low tax rates) </I><BR>
Taiwan's top income tax rate is 40 percent. The tax rate that applies to the average income 
level is only 6 percent. The maximum corporate tax rate is 25 percent. Taiwan also has a 
25 percent capital gains tax and a 5 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Taiwan's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 17.5 percent. Taiwan continues to 
privatize its remaining public companies.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Taiwan's average annual inflation rate for the 1980s was less than 2 percent.<FONT SIZE="-
2">[2]</FONT>  Inflation was 6.7 percent for most of 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Foreign investment is banned in agriculture, cable television, cigarette manufacturing, housing 
construction, liquor manufacturing, and the refining of petroleum. Foreign ownership is 
limited in the mining, shipping, and securities industries.  Companies must use local parts in 
the manufacture of automobiles and motorcycles.  Foreign investment cannot exceed a total 
of $5 billion, and no single foreign entity can invest more than $100 million. Earnings from 
investments can only be remitted from Taiwan once a year. These laws are being 
liberalized to attract more investment. There is an established foreign investment code.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Taiwan places limits on foreign participation in the banking industry. Moreover, the 
privatization program of the country's commercial banks has not been fully implemented. 
Some restrictions still apply to open new banks. Nevertheless, banks are competitive and 
are an important source of capital for Taiwan's expanding economy.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Taiwan maintains a minimum wage policy. In addition, the government requires equal pay for 
men and women. Moreover, regular price monitoring is conducted by the Commodity Price 
Supervisory Board, which is comprised of members from the Ministry of Finance, the 
Ministry of Economic Affairs, the Agricultural Commission, and the Ministry of 
Communications. However, this board does not have the power to directly set prices. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property rights are fully protected in Taiwan.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Entrepreneurs can open a business in Taiwan with little trouble. However, the government has 
established some regulations that impose a slight burden on businesses. Nevertheless, by 
global standards, Taiwan has a low level of regulation.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Because Taiwan has a free economy, its black market is very small.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 1.95</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 3  
Taxation 2.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Lawrence J. Lau and Lawrence R. Klein,<I> Models of Development: A Comparative Study of 
Economic Growth in South Korea and Taiwan</I>, International Center for Economic Growth (San 
Francisco: ICS Press, 1990).<BR>
[2] <I> Ibid.</I>, p. 187.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>



