</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Thailand</TITLE>
<H2>THAILAND</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Thailand could be the next Asian tiger. From 1987 to 1991 its gross domestic product grew 
at around 10 percent annually. The current government of Prime Minister Chuan Likphai is 
committed to continued economic liberalization. Political opponents of the regime are trying to limit 
the expansion of increased foreign investment and may ultimately endanger continued economic 
reforms. Thailand's rapid growth has not been without difficulty. For example, Thailand's roads, 
bridges, and rail systems, have failed to keep up with industrial expansion. And, economic 
expansion has not reached everyone. Most cities have pockets of poverty.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Thailand has an average tariff rate of 9.3 percent. In addition, it has non-tariff barriers in many 
areas. One in particular, called "check prices," prevents imports by assessing tariffs at 
artificially high rates. The tariff on an imported product is assessed not according to its 
current price, but according to the price the last time the product entered the country. If the 
invoice price is lower, the Thai government can impose a tariff rate assessed at the previous 
higher price.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR> 
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Thailand has a top marginal income tax rate of 37 percent. The tax on the average income level 
is 5 percent. Thailand has a top corporate tax rate of 30 percent. Moreover, Thailand has a 
30 percent capital gains tax and a 7 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Thailand's government consumption as percentage of GDP is 9.7 percent, down from 12.4 
percent in 1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of inflation) </I><BR>
Thailand had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 3.7 percent. In 1992, the 
inflation rate increased to 4.1 percent. It ran at about 5.2 percent in 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
There are several restrictions on foreign investment in Thailand.  For example, the government 
restricts foreign entry into such service industries as banking and insurance.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Foreign banks are not permitted to own a majority share of a Thai bank. They also may not 
open branches in Thailand. Domestic banks are prohibited from participating in some 
financial activities like real estate ventures. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Thailand imposes price controls on such items as matches, milk, sugar, toiletries, and vegetable 
oil. it also has a minimum wage. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Expropriation is not likely in Thailand, and its court system adequately protects property rights.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Thailand has a large but efficient bureaucracy. However, because Thai bureaucrats often view 
business as exploitable, they often apply taxes, fines, and charges arbitrarily. These and 
other actions pose a moderate burden on business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Thailand's black market is confined mainly to drugs and prostitution.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.30</TH>  
    
Trade 3				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
