<HTML> 
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"> 
<TITLE>Tunisia</TITLE> 
<H2>TUNISIA</H2> 
<HR SIZE=2> 
 
<P>	Tunisia gained its independence from France in 1956. The government nationalized all  
foreign-owned land in 1964.  The result was continued conflict with France. After suffering under  
unproductive socialist economic policies for over 30 years, Tunisia began to reform its economy in  
the early 1990s. Tunisia has devalued its currency, liberalized trade, and cut government subsidies. 
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif"> 
 
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR> 
Tunisia has an average tariff rate of 19.8 percent.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   All  
imports require a license. Some non-tariff barriers exist on imports of luxury items and  
various spare parts. These restrictions are in the form of quotas which limit imports to a  
predetermined amount. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR> 
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR> 
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR> 
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates) </I><BR> 
Tunisia has a top income tax rate of 35 percent. The average income level is taxed at a rate of  
15 percent. Tunisia has a top corporate tax rate of 35 percent. It also has a 17 percent  
value-added tax and a property tax. 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR> 
Tunisia's government consumes 27 percent of GDP.<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>  
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of inflation) </I><BR> 
Tunisia had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 7.3 percent. Inflation was  
5.8 percent in 1992 and 6 percent in 1993. It was about 4.5 percent for 1994. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR> 
Tunisia is open to foreign investment. It treats domestic and foreign firms the same and offers  
attractive tax holidays to investors. However, Tunisia prevents the ownership of land by  
non-Tunisians.   
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR> 
Banks in Tunisia are heavily controlled by the government. For example, it tries to control the  
value of the currency by keeping a strict control of all interest rates and other banking  
policies. This has created barriers to new bank formation because potential bankers are  
restricted in their ability to establish their own policies. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR> 
Tunisia has a minimum wage and maintains some price controls. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR> 
Tunisia has an efficient and effective legal system. Property rights are relatively secure,  
although foreigners are not allowed to own land. Terrorism from Tunisia's growing radical  
Islamic fundamentalist movement, however, is a threat to private property. 
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR> 
Tunisia has a very efficient and well-functioning bureaucracy. Regulations are for the most part  
applied fairly. However, sanitary, health, and product quality regulations are a minor  
burden for businesses. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of black market activity) </I><BR> 
As the Tunisian market has become more accessible to foreign goods, the black market, while  
still moderately large, is shrinking. 
<P><B>Summary</B><BR> 
  
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.85</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1"> 
<P><B>Endnotes</B> 
<P>[1]  This figure for 1992 is based on the most recent data available from the International Monetary  
Fund. Since Tunisia has made significant progress in reducing trade barriers in 1993 and 1994, this figure  
probably overstates the relative openness of the Tunisian market.<BR> 
[2]  This figure is based on the most recent available data from the World Bank. It represents central  
government expenditure as a percentage of GNP for 1991.
 
</FONT> 
<BR> 
<BR> 
<BR> 
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation 
