<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Turkey</TITLE>
<H2>TURKEY</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Turkey became an independent state in 1923 after the collapse of the Ottoman Empire. 
After decades of one-party rule, a multi-party system was adopted in 1950.  After a military coup in 
1960, the army drafted a new constitution in 1961, starting a trend of continued rule by a series of 
ever-weaker governments. As a result, a growing radical socialist and labor movement emerged. 
Beginning in the 1970s, Turkey became a recipient of large amounts of U.S. foreign aid. This aid 
did little to promote economic growth. In fact, it was often used to postpone badly needed 
economic reforms. Recently, however, Turkey has begun to make reforms. It has lowered taxes, 
increased opportunities for foreign investment, and increased its reliance on market forces.  Despite 
such progress, the nation is still plagued by skyrocketing inflation and huge unemployment rates.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Turkey has an average tariff rate of 5.1 percent. Although most import licenses have been 
eliminated, Turkey requires that importers obtain a certificate before selling their products 
in the country. Although this certificate is relatively easy to get, the procedure is still an 
administrative and financial burden to the importer.  Beyond this, there are no other 
significant restrictions on imports. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR> 
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Turkey has a top marginal income tax rate of 55 percent. The average income level is taxed at a 
rate of 25 percent. Turkey has a top corporate tax rate of 45 percent. It also has a value-
added tax that can reach as high as 23 percent and a social contributions tax. 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Turkey's government consumes around 17.5 percent of the country's GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of inflation) </I><BR>
Turkey's average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 44.7 percent. It was around 
60 percent in 1992 and 1993. It was about 107 percent in 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Turkey is relatively open to foreign investment, but some barriers remain. There are no limits 
on how much of a Turkish business foreign investors may own. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Banks are open to foreign ownership. Over 20 foreign banks have been established. Turkey has 
a very competitive domestic banking market. There is, however, a substantial number of 
state-owned banks. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
There are few official price controls in Turkey. However, prices are indirectly controlled by 
large state-owned corporations whose wholesale prices are controlled by the government. 
Turkey plans to allow most of these corporations to set their own prices. Turkey has a 
minimum wage law.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Expropriation is unlikely. Turkey's legal system, while imperfect, protects most private 
property.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Turkey has reduced the size of the bureaucracy, imposed a performance evaluation test for civil 
servants, and centralized government economic decision-making under the prime minister. 
Its regulations are aimed at providing more freedom for businesses. Turkey now has few 
environmental laws, but more may be added in the future.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Turkey has a rather large black market, especially in such foreign goods as pirated recordings 
and printed material like books and magazines.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.00</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 2  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
