<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Venezuela </TITLE>
<H2>VENEZUELA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Venezuela received its independence from Spain in 1821. It is a multi-party electoral 
democracy. An original member of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), 
Venezuela's economy has relied heavily on oil exports. Venezuela had made some progress toward 
free market reforms. However this began to change when. President Rafael Caldera took office in 
February 1994. Caldera has turned away from free market policies and has restored state controls 
on the economy.
<P><IMG SRC="xxx.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Venezuela has an average tariff rate of about 10 percent. It maintains such non-tariff barriers as 
direct import bans on poultry and pork.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3- (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3- (Moderate tax rates) </I><BR>
Venezuela has a top marginal income tax rate of 30 percent. The tax rate that applies to the 
average income is zero percent. Venezuela has a top corporate tax rate of 30 percent. It has 
a value-added tax of 10 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Venezuela's government consumes around 9 percent of GDP. This is down from 11 percent 
since 1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4- (High level of inflation) </I><BR>
Venezuela's average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 25 percent. This increased 
to 32 percent in 1992. For 1993 and 1994, inflation was estimated to be about 40 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Most industries are open to foreign investment. Yet some significant restrictions remain. A few 
industries in Venezuela can have no more than 20 percent of foreign ownership. Businesses 
that employ over 10 people must be 90 percent owned and operated by Venezuelans.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Most banks in Venezuela are privately owned and operated. There are only a few state-owned 
banks. Banking restrictions on foreign bank branches have largely been removed. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Venezuela maintains a minimum wage. The government has wide authority to impose price 
controls, which remain on foodstuffs, medicines, fuel, and public transportation. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
While private property is a staple of the economy, the government is prone to expropriation, 
and property is not fully protected by the court system.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Opening a business in Venezuela is not difficult. Nevertheless, Venezuela's recent economic 
downturn has brought back some elements of corruption. Thus, some regulations are not 
uniformly applied. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Wherever prices remain state-controlled (as in the transportation services, for example), the 
black market is large.  Moreover, about 40 percent of labor services in Caracas is provided 
by the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.00</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 2  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
