<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - January 8, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 8, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Here's a chilling phrase.  &quot;Lives unworthy of being lived&quot;
-- that's the translation of a German phrase that goes all the
way back to 1920.  That's when influential German doctors advocated
a euthanasia program.  The mentally retarded, people who were
insane, and terribly wounded World War I veterans were the first
victims.  Later this same philosophy was used by Adolph Hitler
and served as the philosophical foundation for the Holocaust.

<p>

Today, the U.S. Supreme Court will hear oral arguments in two
euthanasia cases. It is just weeks before we observe the twenty-fourth
anniversary of the Court's infamous <I>Roe v. Wade</I> decision.
That unjust decision gave us partial-birth abortions and the
death of 30 million unborn children.  And it has seriously undermined
the respect that we should give to the courts.

<p>

America is not Germany.  But we must take care not to remove
those safeguards that have historically protected vulnerable lives.
Remember, the oldest rule in medicine: &quot;Do no harm.&quot;
If we forget it, the so-called right to die will become a right
to be killed.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.<BR>

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwold.html.cgi#current">Last Month's Commentaries</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwdaily.html.cgi#current">This Month's Commentaries</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

<HR SIZE = 3>

<p>

